# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computer-monitor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] 1080p video signals are supported by ATSC standards in the United States and DVB standards in Europe.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Applications of the 1080p standard include television broadcasts, Blu-ray Discs, smartphones, Internet content such as YouTube videos and Netflix TV shows and movies, consumer-grade televisions and projectors, computer monitors and video game consoles.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Small camcorders, smartphones and digital cameras can capture still and moving images in 1080p resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Any display device that advertises 1080p typically refers to the ability to accept a 1080p signal and display it with a native resolution of at least 1080 lines vertically (as well as the ability to upscale lower-resolution material to 1080p).
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] This means that the display is not over-scanning, under-scanning, or reinterpreting the signal to a lower resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] The HD ready 1080p logo program, by DigitalEurope, requires that certified TV sets support 1080p 24 fps, 1080p 25 fps, 1080p 50 fps, and 1080p 60 fps formats, among other requirements, with fps meaning frames per second.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] For live broadcast applications, a high-definition progressive scan format operating at 1080p at 50 or 60 frames per second was being evaluated as a future standard for moving picture acquisition, although 24 fps was used for shooting movies.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Most current revisions of SMPTE 372M, SMPTE 424M and EBU Tech 3299 require YCbCr color space and 4:2:2 chroma subsampling for transmitting 1080p50 (nominally 2.08 Gbit/s) and 1080p60 signal.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] In the United States, the original ATSC standards for HDTV supported 1080p video, but only at the frame rates of 23.976, 24, 25, 29.97 and 30 frames per second (colloquially known as **1080p24**, **1080p25** and **1080p30**).
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Such frame rates require H.264/AVC *High Profile Level 4.2*, while standard HDTV frame rates only require Level 4.0.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] This update is not expected to result in widespread availability of 1080p60 programming, since most of the existing digital receivers in use would only be able to decode the older, less-efficient MPEG-2 codec, and because there is a limited amount of bandwidth for subchannels.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] In Europe, 1080p25 signals have been supported by the DVB suite of broadcasting standards.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] The 1080p50 format is considered to be a future-proof production format and, eventually, a future broadcasting format.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] 1080p50 broadcasting should require the same bandwidth as 1080i50 signal and only 15–20% more than that of 720p50 signal due to increased compression efficiency, though 1080p50 production requires more bandwidth or more efficient codecs such as JPEG 2000, high-bitrate MPEG-2, or H.264/AVC and HEVC.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] EBU requires that legacy MPEG-4 AVC decoders should avoid crashing in the presence of SVC or 1080p50 (and higher resolution) packets.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] The ITU-T BT.2100 standard that includes Advanced 1080p video was subsequently published in July 2016.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] In practice, 1080p typically refers to a 1920 × 1080p raster with a 16:9 picture aspect ratio.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] The following is a list of other resolutions with a picture height of 1080 lines that are sometimes referred as 1080p.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] In the United States, 1080p over-the-air broadcasts are currently available in select stations in some cities in the US via ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations where as ATSC 3.0 is currently rolling out throughout the U.S.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] The majority of the stations that broadcast at 1080p are CBS and NBC stations and affiliates.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] All other stations do not broadcast at 1080p and usually broadcast at 720p60 (including when simulcasting in ATSC 3.0) or 1080i60 (outside of ATSC 3.0) encoded with MPEG-2.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] There is also technical restrictions with ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations that prevent stations from airing at 1080p.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] While converting to ATSC 3.0 is voluntary by TV Stations, there is no word when any of the major networks will consider airing at 1080p in the foreseeable future on a national scale, although they are required to broadcast ATSC signals for at least five years thereafter.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] However, satellite services (e.g., DirecTV, XstreamHD and Dish Network) use the 1080p/24-30 format with MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 encoding for pay-per-view movies that are downloaded in advance via satellite or on-demand via broadband.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] For material that originates from a progressive scanned 24 frame/s source (such as film), MPEG-2 lets the video be coded as 1080p24, irrespective of the final output format.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] These progressively-coded frames are tagged with metadata (literally, fields of the PICTURE header) instructing a decoder how to perform a 3:2 pulldown to interlace them.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] While the formal output of the MPEG-2 decoding process from such stations is 1080i60, the actual content is coded as 1080p24 and can be viewed as such (using a process known as inverse telecine) since no information is lost even when the broadcaster performs the 3:2 pulldown.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] In June 2016, German television stations began broadcasting 1080p50 high-definition video on eight channels via the HEVC-encoded DVB-T2 protocol.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] A total of 40 channels were available on March 29, 2017 (Phase 1).
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Blu-ray Discs are able to hold 1080p HD content, and most movies released on Blu-ray Disc produce a full 1080p HD picture when the player is connected to a 1080p HDTV via an HDMI cable.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Generally this type of video runs at 30 to 40 megabits per second, compared to the 3.5 megabits per second for conventional standard definition broadcasts.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Smartphones with 1080p Full HD display have been available on the market since 2012.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] As of 2014, it is the standard for mid-range to high-end smartphones, with many flagship devices using even higher resolutions, such as Quad HD (1440p) or Ultra HD (2160p).
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Several websites, including YouTube, allow videos to be uploaded in the 1080p format.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] YouTube streams 1080p content at approximately 4 megabits per second compared to Blu-ray's 30 to 40 megabits per second.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Digital distribution services like Hulu and HBO Max also deliver 1080p content, such as movies available on Blu-ray Disc or from broadcast sources.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] This can include distribution services like peer-to-peer websites and public or private tracking networks.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Netflix has been offering high quality 1080p content in the US and other countries through select internet providers since 2013.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] As of 2012, most consumer televisions being sold provide 1080p inputs, mainly via HDMI, and support full high-definition resolutions.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] 1080p resolution is available in all types of television, including plasma, LCD, DLP front and rear projection and LCD projection.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] For displaying film-based 1080i60 signals, a scheme called 3:2 pulldown reversal (reverse telecine) is beginning to appear in some newer 1080p displays, which can produce a true 1080p quality image from film-based 1080i60 programs.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Similarly, 25fps content broadcast at 1080i50 may be deinterlaced to 1080p content with no loss of quality or resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] AV equipment manufacturers have adopted the term *Full HD* to mean a set can display all available HD resolutions up to 1080p.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] The term is misleading, however, because it does not guarantee the set is capable of rendering digital video at all frame rates encoded in source files with 1920 X 1080 pixel resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Most notably, a "Full HD" set is not guaranteed to support the 1080p24 format, leading to consumer confusion.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] DigitalEurope (formerly EICTA) maintains the HD ready 1080p logo program that requires the certified TV sets to support 1080p24, 1080p50, and 1080p60, without overscan/underscan and picture distortion.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Most widescreen cathode-ray tube (CRT) and liquid-crystal display (LCD) monitors can natively display 1080p content.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] For example, widescreen WUXGA monitors support 1920 × 1200 resolution, which can display a pixel for pixel reproduction of the 1080p (1920 × 1080) format.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Additionally, many 23, 24, and 27-inch (690 mm) widescreen LCD monitors use 1920 × 1200 as their native resolution; 30 inch displays can display beyond 1080p at up to 2560 × 1600 (1600p).
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Many 27" monitors have native resolutions of 2560 × 1440 and hence operate at 1440p.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Sony has their first and formerly Vaio 1080p laptop, VPCCB17FG, in 2011, and since Asus also has their first 4K laptop GL502 which was formerly branded Republic of Gamers in 2017, 1080p has also become the nowadays lowest standard for laptops.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] While Microsoft's original Xbox, launched as part of the sixth generation of video game consoles in 2001, could support a 1080i output in limited circumstances, support for 1080p began with the launch of the seventh generation of home video game consoles in 2005.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Both the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 were capable of outputting at 1080p, with only the Wii unable to support the resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] All home video game consoles launched as part of the eighth generation, which began in 2012 with the launch of the Wii U, were capable of 1080p outputs.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Mid-generation hardware revisions and new models introduced by Sony and Microsoft to their respective PlayStation 4 and Xbox One consoles added the capability of outputting at 4K UHD — well beyond 1080p.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Moreover, this mid-generational improvement in computing power also represented a leap in the ability of video game consoles to render gaming content at a 1080p resolution or higher, rather than relying on upscaling.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] This trend continued with the launch of the current ninth generation of video game consoles in 2020, in which both Sony's PlayStation 5 and Microsoft's Xbox Series X were advertised as including 8K UHD support.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] As of 2024, however, neither console yet supports outputting the standard and PlayStation 5 packaging no longer advertises the feature.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] The Nintendo Switch console displays in resolutions up to 1080p when docked, while the successor console, Nintendo Switch 2, displays in 1080p when undocked, and up to 4K when docked.
[src:computer-monitor/1080p] Many cameras—professional and consumer still, action and video cameras, including DSLR cameras—and other devices with built-in cameras such as laptops, smartphones and tablet computers, can capture 1080p24, 1080p25, 1080p30 or 1080p60 video, often encoding it in progressive segmented frame format.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A **3D scanner** can be based on many different technologies, each with its own limitations, advantages and costs.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Many limitations in the kind of objects that can be digitized are still present.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] For example, optical technology may encounter difficulties with dark, shiny, reflective or transparent objects while industrial computed tomography scanning, structured-light 3D scanners, LiDAR and Time-Of-Flight 3D scanners can be used to construct digital 3D models, without destructive testing.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Collected 3D data is useful for a wide variety of applications.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These devices are used extensively by the entertainment industry in the production of movies and video games, including virtual reality.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Other common applications of this technology include augmented reality, motion capture, gesture recognition, robotic mapping, industrial design, orthotics and prosthetics, reverse engineering and prototyping, quality control/inspection and the digitization of cultural artifacts.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The purpose of a 3D scanner is usually to create a 3D model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This 3D model consists of a polygon mesh or point cloud of geometric samples on the surface of the subject.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These points can then be used to extrapolate the shape of the subject (a process called reconstruction).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] If color information is collected at each point, then the colors and textures on the surface of the subject can also be determined.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 3D scanners share several traits with cameras.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Like most cameras, they have a cone-like field of view, and like cameras, they can only collect information about surfaces that are not obscured.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] While a camera collects color information about surfaces within its field of view, a 3D scanner collects distance information about surfaces within its field of view.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The "picture" produced by a 3D scanner describes the distance to a surface at each point in the picture.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This allows the three dimensional position of each point in the picture to be identified.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In some situations, a single scan will not produce a complete model of the subject.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Multiple scans, from different directions are usually helpful to obtain information about all sides of the subject.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These scans have to be brought into a common reference system, a process that is usually called *alignment* or *registration*, and then merged to create a complete 3D model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This whole process, going from the single range map to the whole model, is usually known as the 3D scanning pipeline.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] There are a variety of technologies for digitally acquiring the shape of a 3D object.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The techniques work with most or all sensor types including optical, acoustic, laser scanning, radar, thermal, and seismic.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 3D scan technologies can be split in 2 categories: contact and non-contact.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Non-contact solutions can be further divided into two main categories, active and passive.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] There are a variety of technologies that fall under each of these categories.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Contact 3D scanners work by physically probing (touching) the part and recording the position of the sensor as the probe moves around the part.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Both modern CMMs and Articulated Arms can also be fitted with non-contact laser scanners instead of touch probes.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Active scanners emit some kind of radiation or light and detect its reflection or radiation passing through object in order to probe an object or environment.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Possible types of emissions used include light, ultrasound or x-ray.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The time-of-flight 3D laser scanner is an active scanner that uses laser light to probe the subject.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] At the heart of this type of scanner is a time-of-flight laser range finder.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The laser range finder finds the distance of a surface by timing the round-trip time of a pulse of light.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A laser is used to emit a pulse of light and the amount of time before the reflected light is seen by a detector is measured.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Since the speed of light c is known, the round-trip time determines the travel distance of the light, which is twice the distance between the scanner and the surface.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] If t is the round-trip time, then distance is equal to $\textstyle c\!\cdot \!t/2$ .
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The accuracy of a time-of-flight 3D laser scanner depends on how precisely we can measure the t time: 3.3 picoseconds (approx.) is the time taken for light to travel 1 millimetre.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The laser range finder only detects the distance of one point in its direction of view.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Thus, the scanner scans its entire field of view one point at a time by changing the range finder's direction of view to scan different points.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The view direction of the laser range finder can be changed either by rotating the range finder itself, or by using a system of rotating mirrors.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The latter method is commonly used because mirrors are much lighter and can thus be rotated much faster and with greater accuracy.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Typical time-of-flight 3D laser scanners can measure the distance of 10,000-100,000 points every second.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight devices are also available in a 2D configuration.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This is referred to as a time-of-flight camera.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Triangulation based 3D laser scanners are also active scanners that use laser light to probe the environment.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] With respect to time-of-flight 3D laser scanner the triangulation laser shines a laser on the subject and exploits a camera to look for the location of the laser dot.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Depending on how far away the laser strikes a surface, the laser dot appears at different places in the camera's field of view.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This technique is called triangulation because the laser dot, the camera and the laser emitter form a triangle.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The length of one side of the triangle, the distance between the camera and the laser emitter is known.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The angle of the laser emitter corner is also known.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The angle of the camera corner can be determined by looking at the location of the laser dot in the camera's field of view.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These three pieces of information fully determine the shape and size of the triangle and give the location of the laser dot corner of the triangle.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In most cases a laser stripe, instead of a single laser dot, is swept across the object to speed up the acquisition process.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The use of triangulation to measure distances dates to antiquity.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight range finders are capable of operating over long distances on the order of kilometres.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These scanners are thus suitable for scanning large structures like buildings or geographic features.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A disadvantage is that, due to the high speed of light, measuring the round-trip time is difficult and so the accuracy of the distance measurement is relatively low, on the order of millimetres.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Triangulation range finders, on the other hand, have a range of usually limited to a few meters for reasonably sized devices, but their accuracy is relatively high.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The accuracy of triangulation range finders is on the order of tens of micrometers.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight scanners' accuracy can be lost when the laser hits the edge of an object because the information that is sent back to the scanner is from two different locations for one laser pulse.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The coordinate relative to the scanner's position for a point that has hit the edge of an object will be calculated based on an average and therefore will put the point in the wrong place.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] When using a high resolution scan on an object the chances of the beam hitting an edge are increased and the resulting data will show noise just behind the edges of the object.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Scanners with a smaller beam width will help to solve this problem but will be limited by range as the beam width will increase over distance.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Software can also help by determining that the first object to be hit by the laser beam should cancel out the second.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] At a rate of 10,000 sample points per second, low resolution scans can take less than a second, but high resolution scans, requiring millions of samples, can take minutes for some time-of-flight scanners.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The problem this creates is distortion from motion.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Since each point is sampled at a different time, any motion in the subject or the scanner will distort the collected data.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Thus, it is usually necessary to mount both the subject and the scanner on stable platforms and minimise vibration.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Using these scanners to scan objects in motion is very difficult.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Recently, there has been research on compensating for distortion from small amounts of vibration and distortions due to motion and/or rotation.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Short-range laser scanners can not usually encompass a depth of field more than 1 meter.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] When scanning in one position for any length of time slight movement can occur in the scanner position due to changes in temperature.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] If the scanner is set on a tripod and there is strong sunlight on one side of the scanner then that side of the tripod will expand and slowly distort the scan data from one side to another.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Some laser scanners have level compensators built into them to counteract any movement of the scanner during the scan process.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In a conoscopic system, a laser beam is projected onto the surface and then the immediate reflection along the same ray-path are put through a conoscopic crystal and projected onto a CCD.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The result is a diffraction pattern, that can be frequency analyzed to determine the distance to the measured surface.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The main advantage with conoscopic holography is that only a single ray-path is needed for measuring, thus giving an opportunity to measure for instance the depth of a finely drilled hole.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Hand-held laser scanners create a 3D image through the triangulation mechanism described above: a laser dot or line is projected onto an object from a hand-held device and a sensor (typically a charge-coupled device or position sensitive device) measures the distance to the surface.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Data is collected in relation to an internal coordinate system and therefore to collect data where the scanner is in motion the position of the scanner must be determined.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The position can be determined by the scanner using reference features on the surface being scanned (typically adhesive reflective tabs, but natural features have been also used in research work) or by using an external tracking method.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] External tracking often takes the form of a laser tracker (to provide the sensor position) with integrated camera (to determine the orientation of the scanner) or a photogrammetric solution using 3 or more cameras providing the complete six degrees of freedom of the scanner.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Both techniques tend to use infrared light-emitting diodes attached to the scanner which are seen by the camera(s) through filters providing resilience to ambient lighting.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Data is collected by a computer and recorded as data points within three-dimensional space, with processing this can be converted into a triangulated mesh and then a computer-aided design model, often as non-uniform rational B-spline surfaces.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Hand-held laser scanners can combine this data with passive, visible-light sensors — which capture surface textures and colors — to build (or "reverse engineer") a full 3D model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Structured-light 3D scanners project a pattern of light on the subject and look at the deformation of the pattern on the subject.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The pattern is projected onto the subject using either an LCD projector or other stable light source.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A camera, offset slightly from the pattern projector, looks at the shape of the pattern and calculates the distance of every point in the field of view.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Structured-light scanning is still a very active area of research with many research papers published each year.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Perfect maps have also been proven useful as structured light patterns that solve the correspondence problem and allow for error detection and error correction.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The advantage of structured-light 3D scanners is speed and precision.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Instead of scanning one point at a time, structured light scanners scan multiple points or the entire field of view at once.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Scanning an entire field of view in a fraction of a second reduces or eliminates the problem of distortion from motion.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Some existing systems are capable of scanning moving objects in real-time.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A real-time scanner using digital fringe projection and phase-shifting technique (certain kinds of structured light methods) was developed, to capture, reconstruct, and render high-density details of dynamically deformable objects (such as facial expressions) at 40 frames per second.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Recently, another scanner has been developed.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Different patterns can be applied to this system, and the frame rate for capturing and data processing achieves 120 frames per second.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] It can also scan isolated surfaces, for example two moving hands.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] By utilising the binary defocusing technique, speed breakthroughs have been made that could reach hundreds to thousands of frames per second.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Modulated light 3D scanners shine a continually changing light at the subject.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Usually the light source simply cycles its amplitude in a sinusoidal pattern.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A camera detects the reflected light and the amount the pattern is shifted by determines the distance the light travelled.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Modulated light also allows the scanner to ignore light from sources other than a laser, so there is no interference.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These techniques produce a discrete 3D volumetric representation that can be directly visualised, manipulated or converted to traditional 3D surface by mean of isosurface extraction algorithms.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Passive 3D imaging solutions do not emit any kind of radiation themselves, but instead rely on detecting reflected ambient radiation.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Most solutions of this type detect visible light because it is a readily available ambient radiation.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Other types of radiation, such as infrared could also be used.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Passive methods can be very cheap, because in most cases they do not need particular hardware but simple digital cameras.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Photogrammetry provides reliable information about 3D shapes of physical objects based on analysis of photographic images.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The resulting 3D data is typically provided as a 3D point cloud, 3D mesh or 3D points.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Various software packages are available including PhotoModeler, Geodetic Systems, Autodesk ReCap, RealityCapture and Agisoft Metashape (see comparison of photogrammetry software).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Semi-automatic building extraction from lidar data and high-resolution images is also a possibility.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Again, this approach allows modelling without physically moving towards the location or object.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] From airborne lidar data, digital surface model (DSM) can be generated and then the objects higher than the ground are automatically detected from the DSM.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Based on general knowledge about buildings, geometric characteristics such as size, height and shape information are then used to separate the buildings from other objects.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The extracted building outlines are then simplified using an orthogonal algorithm to obtain better cartographic quality.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Watershed analysis can be conducted to extract the ridgelines of building roofs.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The ridgelines as well as slope information are used to classify the buildings per type.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The buildings are then reconstructed using three parametric building models (flat, gabled, hipped).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Lidar and other terrestrial laser scanning technology offers the fastest, automated way to collect height or distance information. lidar or laser for height measurement of buildings is becoming very promising.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Commercial applications of both airborne lidar and ground laser scanning technology have proven to be fast and accurate methods for building height extraction.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The building extraction task is needed to determine building locations, ground elevation, orientations, building size, rooftop heights, etc.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Most buildings are described to sufficient details in terms of general polyhedra, i.e., their boundaries can be represented by a set of planar surfaces and straight lines.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Further processing such as expressing building footprints as polygons is used for data storing in GIS databases.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Using laser scans and images taken from ground level and a bird's-eye perspective, Fruh and Zakhor present an approach to automatically create textured 3D city models.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This approach involves registering and merging the detailed facade models with a complementary airborne model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The airborne modeling process generates a half-meter resolution model with a bird's-eye view of the entire area, containing terrain profile and building tops.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Ground-based modeling process results in a detailed model of the building facades.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Using the DSM obtained from airborne laser scans, they localize the acquisition vehicle and register the ground-based facades to the airborne model by means of Monte Carlo localization (MCL).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Finally, the two models are merged with different resolutions to obtain a 3D model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Using an airborne laser altimeter, Haala, Brenner and Anders combined height data with the existing ground plans of buildings.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The ground plans of buildings had already been acquired either in analog form by maps and plans or digitally in a 2D GIS.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The project was done in order to enable an automatic data capture by the integration of these different types of information.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Afterwards virtual reality city models are generated in the project by texture processing, e.g. by mapping of terrestrial images.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The project demonstrated the feasibility of rapid acquisition of 3D urban GIS.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Ground plans proved are another very important source of information for 3D building reconstruction.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Compared to results of automatic procedures, these ground plans proved more reliable since they contain aggregated information which has been made explicit by human interpretation.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] For this reason, ground plans, can considerably reduce costs in a reconstruction project.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] An example of existing ground plan data usable in building reconstruction is the Digital Cadastral map, which provides information on the distribution of property, including the borders of all agricultural areas and the ground plans of existing buildings.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Additionally information as street names and the usage of buildings (e.g. garage, residential building, office block, industrial building, church) is provided in the form of text symbols.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] At the moment the Digital Cadastral map is built up as a database covering an area, mainly composed by digitizing preexisting maps or plans.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The point clouds produced by 3D scanners and 3D imaging can be used directly for measurement and visualisation in the architecture and construction world.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Most applications, however, use instead polygonal 3D models, NURBS surface models, or editable feature-based CAD models (aka solid models).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These CAD models describe not simply the envelope or shape of the object, but CAD models also embody the "design intent" (i.e., critical features and their relationship to other features).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] An example of design intent not evident in the shape alone might be a brake drum's lug bolts, which must be concentric with the hole in the centre of the drum.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This knowledge would drive the sequence and method of creating the CAD model; a designer with an awareness of this relationship would not design the lug bolts referenced to the outside diameter, but instead, to the center.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A modeler creating a CAD model will want to include both Shape and design intent in the complete CAD model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Vendors offer different approaches to getting to the parametric CAD model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Some export the NURBS surfaces and leave it to the CAD designer to complete the model in CAD (e.g., Geomagic, Imageware, Rhino 3D).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Others use the scan data to create an editable and verifiable feature based model that is imported into CAD with full feature tree intact, yielding a complete, native CAD model, capturing both shape and design intent (e.g.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] For instance, the market offers various plug-ins for established CAD-programs, such as SolidWorks.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Xtract3D, DezignWorks and Geomagic for SolidWorks allow manipulating a 3D scan directly inside SolidWorks.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Still other CAD applications are robust enough to manipulate limited points or polygon models within the CAD environment (e.g., CATIA, AutoCAD, Revit).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] CT, industrial CT, MRI, or micro-CT scanners do not produce point clouds but a set of 2D slices (each termed a "tomogram") which are then 'stacked together' to produce a 3D representation.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The laser power used for laser scanning equipment in industrial applications is typically less than 1W.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The power level is usually on the order of 200 mW or less but sometimes more.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 3D data acquisition and object reconstruction can be performed using stereo image pairs.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Stereo photogrammetry or photogrammetry based on a block of overlapped images is the primary approach for 3D mapping and object reconstruction using 2D images.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Close-range photogrammetry has also matured to the level where cameras or digital cameras can be used to capture the close-look images of objects, e.g., buildings, and reconstruct them using the very same theory as the aerial photogrammetry.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] An example of software which could do this is Vexcel FotoG 5.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This software has now been replaced by Vexcel GeoSynth.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Another similar software program is Microsoft Photosynth.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A semi-automatic method for acquiring 3D topologically structured data from 2D aerial stereo images has been presented by Sisi Zlatanova.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The process involves the manual digitizing of a number of points necessary for automatically reconstructing the 3D objects.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Each reconstructed object is validated by superimposition of its wire frame graphics in the stereo model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The topologically structured 3D data is stored in a database and are also used for visualization of the objects.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Notable software used for 3D data acquisition using 2D images include e.g.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Agisoft Metashape, RealityCapture, and ENSAIS Engineering College TIPHON (Traitement d'Image et PHOtogrammétrie Numérique).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A method for semi-automatic building extraction together with a concept for storing building models alongside terrain and other topographic data in a topographical information system has been developed by Franz Rottensteiner.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] His approach was based on the integration of building parameter estimations into the photogrammetry process applying a hybrid modeling scheme.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Buildings are decomposed into a set of simple primitives that are reconstructed individually and are then combined by Boolean operators.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Multiple images are used in Zhang's approach to surface reconstruction from multiple images.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A central idea is to explore the integration of both 3D stereo data and 2D calibrated images.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This approach is motivated by the fact that only robust and accurate feature points that survived the geometry scrutiny of multiple images are reconstructed in space.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The density insufficiency and the inevitable holes in the stereo data should then be filled in by using information from multiple images.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The idea is thus to first construct small surface patches from stereo points, then to progressively propagate only reliable patches in their neighborhood from images into the whole surface using a best-first strategy.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The problem thus reduces to searching for an optimal local surface patch going through a given set of stereo points from images.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Multi-spectral images are also used for 3D building detection.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The first and last pulse data and the normalized difference vegetation index are used in the process.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] New measurement techniques are also employed to obtain measurements of and between objects from single images by using the projection, or the shadow as well as their combination.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This technology is gaining attention given its fast processing time, and far lower cost than stereo measurements.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 3D scanning technology has been used to scan space rocks for the European Space Agency.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are used by the entertainment industry to create digital 3D models for movies, video games and leisure purposes.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] They are heavily utilized in virtual cinematography.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In cases where a real-world equivalent of a model exists, it is much faster to scan the real-world object than to manually create a model using 3D modeling software.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Frequently, artists sculpt physical models of what they want and scan them into digital form rather than directly creating digital models on a computer.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are evolving for the use of cameras to represent 3D objects in an accurate manner.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Companies are emerging since 2010 that create 3D portraits of people (3D figurines or 3D selfie).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 3D laser scanning is used by the law enforcement agencies around the world.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Reverse engineering of a mechanical component requires a precise digital model of the objects to be reproduced.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Rather than a set of points a precise digital model can be represented by a polygon mesh, a set of flat or curved NURBS surfaces, or ideally for mechanical components, a CAD solid model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A 3D scanner can be used to digitise free-form or gradually changing shaped components as well as prismatic geometries whereas a coordinate measuring machine is usually used only to determine simple dimensions of a highly prismatic model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These data points are then processed to create a usable digital model, usually using specialized reverse engineering software.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Land or buildings can be scanned into a 3D model, which allows buyers to tour and inspect the property remotely, anywhere, without having to be present at the property.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] There is already at least one company providing 3D scanned virtual real estate tours.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A typical virtual tour Archived 2017-04-27 at the Wayback Machine would consist of dollhouse view, inside view, as well as a floor plan.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The environment at a place of interest can be captured and converted into a 3D model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This model can then be explored by the public, either through a VR interface or a traditional "2D" interface.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This allows the user to explore locations which are inconvenient for travel.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A group of history students at Vancouver iTech Preparatory Middle School created a Virtual Museum by 3D Scanning more than 100 artifacts.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] There have been many research projects undertaken via the scanning of historical sites and artifacts both for documentation and analysis purposes.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The resulting models can be used for a variety of different analytical approaches.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The combined use of 3D scanning and 3D printing technologies allows the replication of real objects without the use of traditional plaster casting techniques, that in many cases can be too invasive for being performed on precious or delicate cultural heritage artifacts.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In an example of a typical application scenario, a gargoyle model was digitally acquired using a 3D scanner and the produced 3D data was processed using MeshLab.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The resulting digital 3D model was fed to a rapid prototyping machine to create a real resin replica of the original object.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] More recently, smartphone-based LiDAR apps have enabled on-site capture of cultural heritage objects; for example, a 1,500-year-old Buddhist stone relief was scanned using a LiDAR-equipped iPhone and the CapCam app, producing a high-density mesh suitable for 3D printing a physical replica.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In 1999, two different research groups started scanning Michelangelo's statues.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Stanford University with a group led by Marc Levoy used a custom laser triangulation scanner built by Cyberware to scan Michelangelo's statues in Florence, notably the David, the Prigioni and the four statues in The Medici Chapel.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The scans produced a data point density of one sample per 0.25 mm, detailed enough to see Michelangelo's chisel marks.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These detailed scans produced a large amount of data (up to 32 gigabytes) and processing the data from his scans took 5 months.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Approximately in the same period a research group from IBM, led by H.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Bernardini scanned the Pietà of Florence acquiring both geometric and color details.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The digital model, result of the Stanford scanning campaign, was thoroughly used in the 2004 subsequent restoration of the statue.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In 2002, David Luebke, et al. scanned Thomas Jefferson's Monticello.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A commercial time of flight laser scanner, the DeltaSphere 3000, was used.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The scanner data was later combined with color data from digital photographs to create the Virtual Monticello, and the Jefferson's Cabinet exhibits in the New Orleans Museum of Art in 2003.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The Virtual Monticello exhibit simulated a window looking into Jefferson's Library.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The exhibit consisted of a rear projection display on a wall and a pair of stereo glasses for the viewer.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The glasses, combined with polarised projectors, provided a 3D effect.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Position tracking hardware on the glasses allowed the display to adapt as the viewer moves around, creating the illusion that the display is actually a hole in the wall looking into Jefferson's Library.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The Jefferson's Cabinet exhibit was a barrier stereogram (essentially a non-active hologram that appears different from different angles) of Jefferson's Cabinet.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The first 3D models of cuneiform tablets were acquired in Germany in 2000.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In 2003 the so-called *Digital Hammurabi project* acquired cuneiform tablets with a laser triangulation scanner using a regular grid pattern having a resolution of 0.025 mm (0.00098 in).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] With the use of high-resolution 3D scanners by the Heidelberg University for tablet acquisition in 2009 the development of the GigaMesh Software Framework began to visualize and extract cuneiform characters from 3D models.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 2.000 3D digitized tablets of the Hilprecht Collection in Jena to create an Open Access benchmark dataset and an annotated collection of 3D models of tablets freely available under CC BY licenses.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A 2009 CyArk 3D scanning project at Uganda's historic Kasubi Tombs, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, using a Leica HDS 4500, produced detailed architectural models of Muzibu Azaala Mpanga, the main building at the complex and tomb of the Kabakas (Kings) of Uganda.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] A fire on March 16, 2010, burned down much of the Muzibu Azaala Mpanga structure, and reconstruction work is likely to lean heavily upon the dataset produced by the 3D scan mission.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In 2005, Gabriele Guidi, et al. scanned the "Plastico di Roma antica", a model of Rome created in the last century.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Neither the triangulation method, nor the time of flight method satisfied the requirements of this project because the item to be scanned was both large and contained small details.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] They found though, that a modulated light scanner was able to provide both the ability to scan an object the size of the model and the accuracy that was needed.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The modulated light scanner was supplemented by a triangulation scanner which was used to scan some parts of the model.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The Smithsonian Institution has a project called Smithsonian X 3D notable for the breadth of types of 3D objects they are attempting to scan.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] These include small objects such as insects and flowers, to human sized objects such as Amelia Earhart's Flight Suit to room sized objects such as the Gunboat Philadelphia to historic sites such as Liang Bua in Indonesia.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Also of note the data from these scans is being made available to the public for free and downloadable in several data formats.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are used to capture the 3D shape of a patient in orthotics and dentistry.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] It gradually supplants tedious plaster cast.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] CAD/CAM software are then used to design and manufacture the orthosis, prosthesis or dental implants.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The chairside systems are designed to facilitate the 3D scanning of a preparation *in vivo* and produce the restoration (such as a Crown, Onlay, Inlay or Veneer).
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Creation of 3D models for anatomy and biology education and cadaver models for educational neurosurgical simulations.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The digitalisation of real-world objects is of vital importance in various application domains.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This method is especially applied in industrial quality assurance to measure the geometric dimension accuracy.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Industrial processes such as assembly are complex, highly automated and typically based on CAD (computer-aided design) data.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The problem is that the same degree of automation is also required for quality assurance.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] It is, for example, a very complex task to assemble a modern car, since it consists of many parts that must fit together at the very end of the production line.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The optimal performance of this process is guaranteed by quality assurance systems.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Especially the geometry of the metal parts must be checked in order to assure that they have the correct dimensions, fit together and finally work reliably.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Within highly automated processes, the resulting geometric measures are transferred to machines that manufacture the desired objects.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Due to mechanical uncertainties and abrasions, the result may differ from its digital nominal.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] In order to automatically capture and evaluate these deviations, the manufactured part must be digitised as well.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] For this purpose, 3D scanners are applied to generate point samples from the object's surface which are finally compared against the nominal data.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The process of comparing 3D data against a CAD model is referred to as CAD-Compare, and can be a useful technique for applications such as determining wear patterns on moulds and tooling, determining accuracy of final build, analysing gap and flush, or analysing highly complex sculpted surfaces.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] At present, laser triangulation scanners, structured light and contact scanning are the predominant technologies employed for industrial purposes, with contact scanning remaining the slowest, but overall most accurate option.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Nevertheless, 3D scanning technology offers distinct advantages compared to traditional touch probe measurements.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] White-light or laser scanners accurately digitize objects all around, capturing fine details and freeform surfaces without reference points or spray.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] The entire surface is covered at record speed without the risk of damaging the part.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Graphic comparison charts illustrate geometric deviations of full object level, providing deeper insights into potential causes.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] After the data has been collected, the acquired (and sometimes already processed) data from images or sensors needs to be reconstructed.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] This may be done in the same program or in some cases, the 3D data needs to be exported and imported into another program for further refining, and/or to add additional data.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Such additional data could be GPS-location data.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] After the reconstruction, the data might be directly implemented into a local (GIS) map or a worldwide map such as Google Earth or Apple Maps.
[src:computer-monitor/3d-scanning] Several software packages are used in which the acquired (and sometimes already processed) data from images or sensors is imported.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The 4K television market share increased as prices fell dramatically throughout 2013 and 2014.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The term **4K** is generic and refers to any resolution with a horizontal pixel count of approximately 4,000.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Several different 4K resolutions have been standardized by various organizations.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] 4K resolution is approximately 8 million pixels, which is 4 times as many as 1080p.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2005, Digital Cinema Initiatives (DCI), a prominent standards organization in the cinema industry, published the **Digital Cinema System Specification**.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This specification establishes standardized 2K and 4K container formats for digital cinema production, with resolutions of 2048 × 1080 and 4096 × 2160 respectively.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] 2K distributions can have a frame rate of either 24 or 48 FPS, while 4K distributions must have a frame rate of 24 FPS.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Some articles claim that the terms **2K** and **4K** were coined by DCI and refer exclusively to the 2K and 4K formats defined in the DCI standard.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] However, usage of these terms in the cinema industry predates the publication of the DCI standard, and they are generally understood as casual terms for any resolution approximately 2000 or 4000 pixels in width, rather than names for specific standard resolutions.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2007, the Society of Motion Picture and Television Engineers published *SMPTE ST 2036-1*, which defines parameters for two UHDTV systems called **UHDTV1** and **UHDTV2**.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2012, the International Telecommunication Union, Radiocommunication Sector published Recommendation BT.2020, also known as the Ultra High Definition Television (UHDTV) standard.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] It adopts the same image parameters defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Although the UHDTV standard does not define any official names for the formats it defines, ITU typically uses the terms **4K**, **4K UHD**, or **4K UHDTV** to refer to the 3840 × 2160 system in public announcements and press releases (**8K** for the 7680 × 4320 system).
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In some of ITU's other standards documents, the terms **UHDTV1** and **UHDTV2** are used as shorthand.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In October 2012, the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) announced its definition of the term **Ultra High-Definition** (or **Ultra HD**) for use with marketing consumer display devices.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The CEA definition does allow manufacturers to use other terms—such as **4K**—alongside the Ultra HD logo.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Since the resolution in CEA's definition is only a minimum requirement, displays with higher resolutions such as 4096 × 2160 or 5120 × 2880 also qualify as "Ultra HD" displays, provided they meet the other requirements.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Some 4K resolutions, like 3840 × 2160, are often casually referred to as **2160p**.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The term **2160p** could be applied to any format with a height of 2160 pixels, but it is most commonly used in reference to the 4K UHDTV resolution of 3840 × 2160 due to its association with the well-known 720p and 1080p HDTV formats.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Although 3840 × 2160 is both a 4K resolution and a 2160p resolution, these terms cannot always be used interchangeably since not all 4K resolutions are 2160 pixels tall, and not all 2160p resolutions are ≈4000 pixels wide.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] However, some companies have begun using the term "4K" to describe devices with support for a 2160p resolution, even if it is not close to 4000 pixels wide.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] For example, many "4K" dash cams only support a resolution of 2880 × 2160 (4∶3); although this is a 2160p resolution, it is not a 4K resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Conversely, Samsung released a 5120 × 2160 (64∶27) TV, but marketed it as a "4K" TV despite its 5K-class resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2015, LG Display announced the implementation of a new technology called M+, which is the addition of white subpixels along with the regular RGB dots in their IPS panel technology.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The media and internet users later called this "RGBW" TVs because of the white sub pixel.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Most of the new M+ technology was employed on 4K TV sets, which led to a controversy after tests showed that the addition of a white subpixel replacing the traditional RGB structure would reduce the resolution by around 25%.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] After tests done by Intertek in which the technical aspects of LG M+ TVs were analyzed and they concluded that "the addressable resolution display is 2,880 X 2,160 for each red, green, blue", in other words, the LG TVs were technically 2.8K as it became known in the controversy.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This negatively impacts the rendering of text, making it a bit fuzzier, which is especially noticeable when a TV is used as a PC monitor.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2019, Sony was granted the CinemaWide trademark by the European Union Intellectual Property Office (EUIPO), in which the trademark covers 'Class 9' electronic devices, including smartphones.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Sony Xperia smartphones are the most widely known products that equipped with CinemaWide 4K display, such as Xperia 1, Xperia 1 II, Xperia 1 III, Xperia 1 IV and Xperia 1 V.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Video sharing website YouTube and the television industry have adopted 3840 × 2160 as their 4K standard.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] As of 2014, 4K content from major broadcasters remained limited.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] By late 2014, 4K content was becoming more widely available online, including on Apple TV, YouTube, Netflix, Hulu, and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] By 2013, some UHDTV models were available to general consumers in the range of US$600.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] As of 2015, prices on smaller computer and television panels had dropped below US$400.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] On March 26, 2013, the Advanced Television Systems Committee announced new proposals of a new standard called ATSC 3.0 which would implement UHD broadcasts at resolutions of up to 3840 × 2160 or 7680 × 4320.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The standard would also include framerates of up to 120 Hz, HEVC encoding, wide color gamut, as well as high dynamic range.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2014, the Digital Video Broadcasting Project released a new set of standards intended to guide the implementation of high-resolution content in broadcast television.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Dubbed **DVB-UHDTV**, it establishes two standards, known as **UHD-1** (for 4K content) and **UHD-2** (for 8K content).
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] These standards use resolutions of 3840 × 2160 and 7680 × 4320 respectively, with framerates of up to 60 Hz, color depth up to 10 bpc (30 bit/px), and HEVC encoding for transmission.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] DVB is currently focusing on the implementation of the UHD-1 standard.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] DVB finalized **UHD-1 Phase 2** in 2016, with the introduction of service by broadcasters expected in 2017.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] UHD-1 Phase 2 adds features such as high dynamic range (using HLG and PQ at 10 or 12 bits), wide color gamut (BT.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] As of February 2025, both YouTube and Vimeo support high-resolution video uploads, with maximum resolutions of 4096 × 2304 pixels (approximately 9.4 megapixels) and 4096 × 2160 pixels (approximately 8.8 megapixels), respectively.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The growing availability of 4K content across streaming platforms like Netflix, Amazon Prime Video, and YouTube has made it more accessible to consumers.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Vimeo's 4K content is currently limited to mostly nature documentaries and tech coverage.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC or H.265) facilitates streaming of 4K content at bitrates between 20 and 30 Mbit/s, offering efficient compression without significant quality loss.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In January 2014, Naughty America launched the first adult video service streaming in 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In February 2025, Super Bowl LIX was broadcast in 4K resolution with Dolby Vision HDR and Dolby Atmos sound for the first time.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Fox aired the game, and it was also available for free streaming in 4K on Tubi, marking a significant milestone in sports broadcasting.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The first mobile phones to be able to record at 2160p (3840 × 2160) were released in late 2013, including the Samsung Galaxy Note 3, which is able to record 2160p at 30 frames per second.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In the year 2014, the OnePlus One was released with the option to record DCI 4K (4096 × 2160) at 24 frames per second, as well as LG G3 and Samsung Galaxy Note 4 with optical image stabilization.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In the year 2015, Apple announced the iPhone 6s was released with the 12 megapixel camera that has the option to record 4K at 25 or 30 frames per second.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In the years 2017 and 2018, mobile phone chipsets reached sufficient processing power that mobile phone vendors started releasing mobile phones that allow recording 2160p footage at 60 frames per second for a smoother and more realistic appearance.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] iMac with Retina Display (2014) is one of the earliest computers that utilise 4K widescreen.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 1981, the NEC μPD7220 computer graphics processor supported monochrome resolutions up to 4096×1024p (progressive scan) or 4096×2048i (interlaced).
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 1984, Hitachi's ARTC HD63484 graphics processor supported monochrome resolutions up to 4096×2048p (progressive scan) or 4096×4096i (interlaced), targeted at the bit-mapped desktop publishing market.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2000, JVC introduced the first 4K digital cinema video projector using D-ILA technology.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The first commercially available 4K camera for cinematographic purposes was the Dalsa Origin, released in 2003.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Sony began offering 4K digital cinema projectors in 2004.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] 4K digital projectors were introduced to movie theaters in 2005, but most theaters continued using analog movie projectors until 4K digital projectors eventually replaced them by 2011.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] 4K streaming technology was developed during the mid-to-late 2000s by several research groups in universities around the world, such as University of California, San Diego, CALIT2, Keio University and Naval Postgraduate School.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] They realized several demonstrations in venues such as IGrid in 2004 and CineGrid.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] YouTube began supporting 4K for video uploads in 2010 as a result of leading manufacturers producing 4K cameras.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Users could view 4K video by selecting "Original" from the quality settings until December 2013, when the 2160p option appeared in the quality menu.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In November 2013, YouTube began to use the VP9 video compression standard, saying that it was more suitable for 4K than High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC).
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Google, which owns YouTube, developed VP9.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The first 4K home theater projector was released by Sony in 2012.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Despite this, as of 2023, there are not many finished films with 4K resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Even for movies and TV shows shot using 6K or 8K cameras, almost all finished films are edited in HD resolution and enlarged to fit a 4K format.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Sony is one of the leading studios promoting UHDTV content, as of 2013 offering a little over 70 movie and television titles via digital download to a specialized player that stores and decodes the video.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The large files (≈40 GB), distributed through consumer broadband connections, raise concerns about data caps.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2014, Netflix began streaming *House of Cards*, *Breaking Bad*, and "some nature documentaries" at 4K to compatible televisions with an HEVC decoder.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Most 4K televisions sold in 2013 did not natively support HEVC, with most major manufacturers announcing support in 2014.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Amazon Studios began shooting their full-length original series and new pilots with 4K resolution in 2014.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] They are now currently available through Amazon Video.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In March 2016 the first players and discs for Ultra HD Blu-ray—a physical optical disc format supporting 4K resolution and high-dynamic-range video (HDR) at 60 frames per second—were released.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] On August 2, 2016, Microsoft released the Xbox One S, which supports 4K streaming and has an Ultra HD Blu-ray disc drive, but does not support 4K gaming.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] On November 10, 2016, Sony released the PlayStation 4 Pro, which supports 4K streaming and gaming, though many games use checkerboard rendering or are upscaled 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] On November 7, 2017, Microsoft released the Xbox One X, which supports 4K streaming and gaming, though not all games are rendered at native 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Though the price of home cinema viewing devices began to drop rapidly from 2013, the digital video projector market saw limited expansion as very few manufacturers had fully 4K-capable lineups.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Native 4K projectors remained priced in the five-figure range well into 2015, only falling below US$10,000 later that year.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Sony was the sole major manufacturer offering a comprehensive 4K projection solution as of 2015.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Critics argue that, at typical direct-view panel sizes and viewing distances, the extra pixels of 4K are unnecessary for normal human vision.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In contrast, home cinema projectors use larger screens without necessarily increasing the viewing distance to match the scale.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This technology reached its fourth generation in 2016.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] JVC applied this technology to create an 8K flight simulation system for Boeing, meeting the visual acuity limits of 20/25.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The first pixel-shifted 4K UHD projectors adopted by the market are Optoma, BenQ, Dell, et al., for those adopt a 2718×1528 pixel structure.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The amount of data these projectors process is true 4K, but they overlap the pixels, which is what pixel shifting is.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In fact, each of those pixels is far larger.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In fact, each one has 50% more area than true 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This way, they project a pixel and shift it up to the right by a half diameter and project it again with modified data—the second pixel overlaid on the first.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This would result in adjacent red and green pixels effectively forming yellow, with a fringe on one side of red, on the other of green—except that the fringe takes on another color as the next line of pixels overlaps too.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] 4K UHD or 1080p pixel shifting cannot reveal the fine detail of a true 4K projector such as those Sony ships in the business, education, and home markets.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] While projecting UHD, it might look as though the pixel structures would have 1/4 the area of 1080p; it just doesn't happen with pixel shifting.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] That much resolution is only carried by a true 4K projector.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This is why "true" 4K costs so much more than 4K UHD projectors that have more or less similar feature sets.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] They produce smaller pixels, finer resolution—no loss of detail or color from the overlapping pixels.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This is in stark contrast to the small variation in the aspect ratio difference, which would be capable of being noticeable in a few companies, such as Kaleidescape, offering media servers that enable 4K UHD Blu-ray movies with a wide dynamic range in a home theater.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In November 2014, American satellite provider DirecTV (owned by AT&T) became the first pay-TV provider to offer access to 4K content, although limited to selected video-on-demand films.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In August 2015, British sports network BT Sport launched a 4K feed, with its first broadcast being the 2015 FA Community Shield football match.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Two production units were used, producing the traditional broadcast in high-definition, and a separate 4K broadcast.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] As the network did not want to mix 4K footage with upconverted HD footage, this telecast did not feature traditional studio segments at pre-game or half-time, but those hosted from the stadium by the match commentators using a 4K camera.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] BT envisioned that if viewers wanted to watch studio analysis, they would switch to the HD broadcast and then back for the game.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Footage was compressed using H.264 encoders and transmitted to BT Tower, where it was then transmitted back to BT Sport studios and decompressed for distribution, via 4K-compatible BT TV set-top boxes on an eligible BT Infinity internet plan with at least a 25 Mbit/s connection.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In late 2015 and January 2016, three of Canada's television providers – including Quebec-based Vidéotron, Ontario-based Rogers Cable, and Bell Fibe TV, announced that they would begin to offer 4K compatible set-top boxes that can stream 4K content to subscribers over gigabit internet service.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Bell Media announced via its TSN division a slate of 4K telecasts to begin on January 20, 2016, including selected Toronto Raptors games and regional NHL games.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] On January 14, 2016, in cooperation with BT Sport, Sportsnet broadcast the first ever NBA game produced in 4K – a Toronto Raptors/Orlando Magic game at O2 Arena in London, England.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] On January 20, also during a Raptors game, TSN presented the first live 4K telecast produced in North America.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Three days later, Sportsnet presented the first NHL game in 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] For the opening game of the 2016 Toronto Blue Jays season, Dome constructed "Trillium" – a production truck integrating both 4K and 1080i high-definition units.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Bell Media's CTV also broadcast the 2016 Juno Awards in 4K as the first awards show presented in the format.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In February 2016, Spanish-language Univision trialed 4K by producing a closed-circuit TV broadcast of a football friendly between the national teams of Mexico and Senegal from Miami (America) in the format.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The broadcast was streamed privately to several special viewing locations.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Univision aimed to develop a 4K streaming app to publicly televise the final of Copa América Centenario in 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In March 2016, DirecTV and CBS Sports announced that they would produce the "Amen Corner" supplemental coverage from the Masters golf tournament in 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In late 2016, Telus TV announced that they would begin to offer 4K compatible set-top boxes.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] After having trialed the technology in limited matches at the 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup, and the 2014 FIFA World Cup (via private tests and public viewings in the host city of Rio de Janeiro), the 2018 FIFA World Cup was the first FIFA World Cup in which all matches were produced in 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Host Broadcasting Services stated that at least 75% of the broadcast cut on each match would come from 4K cameras (covering the majority of main angles), with instant replays and some camera angles being upconverted from 1080p sources.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] These broadcasts were made available from selected rightsholders, such as the BBC in the UK, and selected television providers in the United States.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Technical limitations in distributing 4K broadcasts (including the increased cost of 4K-compatible production equipment) have led to some broadcasters deciding against the format in favour of emphasizing 1080p/HDR broadcasts instead.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] After having broadcast UEFA Euro and the Champions League final in the format, UEFA discontinued 4K coverage for both in 2024, as broadcasters elected to put resources behind HDR and other on-air features instead.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Some U.S. broadcasters, such as CBS Sports, Fox Sports, and USA Network have broadcast events promoted as having "4K" feeds, but are actually 1080p/HDR broadcasts upconverted to 4K.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] For the 2024 Summer Olympics, USA Network's "4K" coverage was sourced from host broadcaster Olympic Broadcasting Services (OBS) in 4K, but downconverted to 1080p when received by NBC Sports' studios, and then upconverted to 4K for distribution.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The resolution of 3840 × 2160 is the dominant 4K resolution in the consumer media and display industries.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This is the resolution of the UHDTV1 format defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1, as well as the 4K UHDTV format defined by ITU-R in Rec.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] 2020, and is also the minimum resolution for CEA's definition of **Ultra HD** displays and projectors.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The resolution of 3840 × 2160 was also chosen by the DVB project for their 4K broadcasting standard, UHD-1.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This resolution has an aspect ratio of 16∶9, with 8,294,400 total pixels.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] It is exactly double the horizontal and vertical resolution of 1080p (1920 × 1080) for a total of 4 times as many pixels, and triple the horizontal and vertical resolution of 720p (1280 × 720) for a total of 9 times as many pixels.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] It is sometimes referred to as "2160p", based on the naming patterns established by the previous 720p and 1080p HDTV standards.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In 2013, televisions capable of displaying UHD resolutions were seen by consumer electronics companies as the next trigger for an upgrade cycle after a lack of consumer interest in 3D television.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This resolution is used mainly in digital cinema production, and has a total of 8,847,360 pixels with an aspect ratio of 256∶135 (≈19∶10).
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] It was standardized as the resolution of the 4K container format defined by Digital Cinema Initiatives in the Digital Cinema System specification, and is the native resolution of all DCI-compliant 4K digital projectors and monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The DCI specification allows several different resolutions for the content inside the container, depending on the desired aspect ratio.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The DCI 4K standard has twice the horizontal and vertical resolution of DCI 2K (2048 × 1080), with four times as many pixels overall.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Digital movies made in 4K may be produced, scanned, or stored in a number of other resolutions depending on what storage aspect ratio is used.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] In the digital cinema production chain, a resolution of 4096 × 3112 is often used for acquiring "open gate" or anamorphic input material, a resolution based on the historical resolution of scanned Super 35 mm film.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] The main advantage of recording video at the 4K standard is that fine spatial detail is resolved well.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Individual still frames extracted from 3840×2160-pixel video footage can act as 8.3 megapixel still photographs, while only 2.1 megapixels at 1080p and 0.9 megapixels at 720p.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] If the final video resolution is reduced to 2K from a 4K recording, more detail is apparent than would have been achieved from a native 2K recording.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Increased fineness and contrast is then possible with output to DVD and Blu-ray.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Some cinematographers record at 4K with the Super 35 film format to offset any resolution loss that may occur during video processing.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Many consumer electronics such as mobile phones store video footage in Y′CBCR format with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling, which records color information at only one quarter the resolution as the brightness information.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] For 3840 × 2160 video, this means that the color information is only stored at 1920 × 1080.
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] Consumer cameras and mobile phones record 2160p footage at much higher bit rates (usually 50 to 100 Mbit/s) than 1080p (usually 10 to 30 Mbit/s).
[src:computer-monitor/4k-resolution] This higher bit rate reduces the visibility of compression artifacts, even if viewed on monitors with a lower resolution than 2160p.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] 8K display resolution is the successor to 4K resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] TV manufacturers pushed to make 4K a new standard by 2017.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] At CES 2012, the first prototype 8K TVs were unveiled by Japanese electronics corporation Sharp.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The feasibility of a fast transition to this new standard is questionable in view of the absence of broadcasting resources.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In 2018, Strategy Analytics predicted that 8K-ready devices will still only account for 3% of UHD TVs by 2023 with global sales of 11 million units a year.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] However, TV manufacturers remain optimistic as the 4K market grew much faster than expected, with actual sales exceeding projections nearly six-fold in 2016.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In 2013, a transmission network's capability to carry HDTV resolution was limited by internet speeds and relied on satellite broadcast to transmit the high data rates.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The demand is expected to drive the adoption of video compression standards and to place significant pressure on physical communication networks in the near future.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In 2018, few cameras had the capability to shoot video in 8K, NHK being one of the few companies to have created a small broadcasting camera with an 8K image sensor.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] By 2018, Red Digital Cinema camera company had delivered three 8K cameras in both a Full Frame sensor and Super 35 sensor.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In 1986, Sony introduced a smectic light valve LCD laser projector that could display high resolutions up to 8K resolution (8000×10,000).
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In 1995, Japan's public broadcaster NHK was the first to start research and development of 4320p resolution, with the Super Hi-Vision system intended as a successor to their Hi-Vision HDTV system.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] 8K Ultra HDTV (UHDTV) was first demonstrated by NHK, JVC and Ikegami Tsushinki researchers with the Super Hi‑Vision system in January 2003.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The format was standardized by SMPTE in October 2007.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The interface was standardized by SMPTE in August 2010 and recommended as the international standard for television by ITU-R in 2012.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] Followed by public displays at electronics shows and screenings of 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi and public viewings in February 2014 and the FIFA World Cup in Brazil in June 2014 using HEVC with partners AstroDesign and Ikegami Electronics.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] On January 6, 2015, the MHL Consortium announced the release of the superMHL specification which will support 8K resolution at 120 fps, 48-bit video, the Rec.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] 2020 color space, high dynamic range support, a 32-pin reversible superMHL connector, and power charging of up to 40 watts.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] On March 1, 2016, the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) unveiled DisplayPort 1.4, a new format that allows the use of 8K resolution (7680 × 4320) at 60 Hz with HDRR and 32 audio channels through USB-C.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] On January 4, 2017, the HDMI Forum announced HDMI 2.1 featuring support for 8K video with HDR, which will be "released early in Q2 2017".
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] 8K Association Formed at CES 2019 to Help Develop 8K Ecosystem.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In early February 2020, Samsung Electronics announced during their Unpacked event that their Samsung Galaxy S20 can video record in 8K, which uses 600 MB of storage per minute.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] On April 6, 2013, Astrodesign Inc. announced the AH-4800, capable of recording 8K resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In April 2015, it was announced by Red that their newly unveiled Red Weapon VV is also capable of recording 8K footage.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In October 2016, they announced two additional 8K cameras, Red Weapon 8K S35 and Red Epic-W 8K S35.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The Red Weapon Dragon VV has been discontinued as of October 7, 2017, when Red unveiled the Red Weapon Monstro VV, their fourth camera capable of shooting 8K, with additional improvements in dynamic range and noise reduction, among other features.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In May 2019, mobile phone vendors started releasing the first mobile phones with 8K video recording capabilities, such as the ZTE Nubia Red Magic 3 series.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] This is enabled by the sufficient resolution of image sensors used in mobile phones, and by the sufficient chipset performance.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] However, mobile phones with up to 5K (2880p) or 6K (3240p) video cameras have never been released.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In 2007, the original 65 mm negative of the 1992 film *Baraka* was re-scanned at 8K with a film scanner built specifically for the job at FotoKem Laboratories, and used to remaster the 2008 Blu-ray release.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] According to Grover Crisp, executive VP of restoration at Sony Pictures, the new 8K scan has such high resolution that when examined, showed a series of fine concentric lines in a pattern "reminiscent of a fingerprint" near the top of the frame.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] This was caused by the film emulsion melting and cracking in the desert heat during production.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] Sony had to hire a third party to minimize or eliminate the rippling artifacts in the new restored version.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] On May 17, 2013, the Franklin Institute premiered *To Space and Back*, an 8K×8K, 60 fps, 3D video running approximately 25 minutes.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] During its first run at the Fels Planetarium it was played at 4K, 60 fps.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In November 2013, NHK screened the experimental-drama short film "The Chorus" at Tokyo Film Festival which was filmed in 8K and 22.2 sound format.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] On May 1, 2015, an 8K abstract computer animation was screened at the Filmatic Festival at the University of California, San Diego.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The work was created as an assignment in the VIS 40/ICAM 40 Introduction to Computing in the Arts class taught at UCSD by Associate Teaching Professor Brett Stalbaum during the winter quarter of 2015, with each student producing three hundred 8192 × 4800 pixel frames.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The work's music soundtrack was composed by Mark Matamoros.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] On January 6, 2016, director James Gunn stated that the 2017 film *Guardians of the Galaxy Vol.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] 2* would be the first feature film to be shot in 8K, using the Red Weapon 8K VV.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The movie was shot with 8K cameras (and partially with 4K cameras), although the digital intermediate of the movie is in a lower resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] Japanese public broadcaster NHK began research and development on 8K in 1995, having spent over $1 billion on R&D since then.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] Codenamed *Super Hi-Vision* (named after its old Hi-Vision analog HDTV system), NHK also was simultaneously working on the development of 22.2 channel surround sound audio.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The world's first 8K television was unveiled by Sharp at the Consumer Electronics Show (CES) in 2012.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] Ultimately, about 200 hours of material from the Tokyo Olympics, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were broadcast in 8K (on the NHK BS8K channel).
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The specification for an 8K Blu-ray format was also completed by the Blu-ray Disc Association for use in Japan by December 2017.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] As of the end of 2024, there are no standalone Blu-ray players certified as 8K capable (even though PC Blu-ray drives able to read 100 GB and 128 GB discs are sold commercially), and no home video releases in 8K on physical media by any major studio.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] On December 1, 2018, NHK launched BS8K, a broadcast channel transmitting at 8K resolution.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] Documentaries constitute a large part of that channel's programming.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] Feature films shown in 8K on that channel include *2001: A Space Odyssey* (1968) and *My Fair Lady* (1964); in both cases, 70 mm analog prints were used as a basis for the remastered 8K version.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] New productions filmed with digital 8K cameras have also been aired in 8K on that channel; they include the Edo period drama *Kikyo – The Return* and the WWII dramas *Wife of a Spy* and *Gift of Fire*.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In Germany, the third season of *Das Boot* (a historical drama TV series set on a Nazi submarine) was made available in 8K on the Samsung TV Plus streaming service.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] In China, the state-owned CMG conglomerate launched a TV channel broadcasting at 8K resolution, known as CCTV-8K.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] Test broadcasts started in 2021 while the official launch was in 2022.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The Sony PlayStation 5 Pro generates 8K graphics and output, making it the first and only game console to do so, though as of October 2025 no full 8K games for it have publicly released.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] The GeForce RTX 3090, released in September 2020 at an MSRP of $1499, was marketed by Nvidia as the first graphics card capable of 8K 60 fps HDR gaming, recording, and streaming with ShadowPlay on PCs.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] However, only its successor, the GeForce RTX 4090, is often regarded as the first graphics card to achieve playable frame rates at 8K in many modern titles.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] This is the resolution of the **UHDTV2** format defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1, as well as the **8K UHDTV** format defined in ITU-R BT.2020.
[src:computer-monitor/8k-resolution] It was also chosen by the DVB project as the resolution for their 8K broadcasting standard, **UHD-2**.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] **alternate frame sequencing**, **alternate image**, **AI**, **alternating field**, **field sequential** or **eclipse method**) is a technique for displaying stereoscopic 3D images.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Modern active shutter 3D systems generally use liquid crystal shutter glasses (also called "LC shutter glasses" or "active shutter glasses").
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Each eye's glass contains a liquid crystal layer which has the property of becoming opaque when voltage is applied, being otherwise transparent.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The glasses are controlled by a timing signal that allows the glasses to alternately block one eye, and then the other, in synchronization with the refresh rate of the screen.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The timing synchronization to the video equipment may be achieved via a wired signal, or wirelessly by either an infrared or radio frequency (e.g.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Historic systems also used spinning discs, for example the Teleview system.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Active shutter 3D systems are used to present 3D films in some theaters, and they can be used to present 3D images on CRT, plasma, LCD, projectors and other types of video displays.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Although virtually all ordinary unmodified video and computer systems can be used to display 3D by adding a plug-in interface and active shutter glasses, disturbing levels of flicker or ghosting may be apparent with systems or displays not designed for such use.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The rate of alternation required to eliminate noticeable flicker depends on image brightness and other factors, but is typically well over 30 image pair cycles per second, the maximum possible with a 60 Hz display.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] A 120 Hz display, allowing 60 images per second per eye, is widely accepted as flicker-free.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Crosstalk is the leakage of frames between left eye and right eye.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] LCDs have exhibited this problem more often than plasma and DLP displays, due to slower pixel response time.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] LCDs that utilize a strobe backlight, such as nVidia's LightBoost, reduce crosstalk.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] This is done by turning off the backlight between refreshes, while waiting for the shutter glasses to switch eyes, and also for the LCD panel to finish pixel transitions.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The **M-3DI Standard** was a cross-manufacturer standardization initiative to increase compatibility of LC (Active) Shutter Glasses led by Panasonic in collaboration with XpanD 3D and announced in March 2011.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] It aimed to increase acceptance of 3D products by consumers by extending the agreement to various manufacturers of 3D TV, computers, notebooks, home projectors, and cinema hardware.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] As of April 2011, the agreement was joined by Hitachi, Changhong, Funai, Hisense, Mitsubishi Electric, Epson, ViewSonic, and SIM2 Multimedia S.p.A.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In August of the same year, M-3DI was superseded by another agreement, named "**Full HD 3D Glasses Initiative**", formed between Panasonic, Samsung, Sony, Sharp Corporation, TCL Technology, Toshiba and Philips.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The standardization agreement comprised consumer products including televisions, computers and projectors, also based on XpanD 3D's technology.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Field Sequential has been used in video games, VHS and VHD movies and is often referred to as HQFS for DVDs, these systems use wired or wireless LCS glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The Sensio format was used with DVDs using wireless LCS glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Each different active 3D shutter glasses implementation can operate in their own manufacturer-set frequency to match the refresh rate of the display or projector.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Therefore, to achieve compatibility across different brands, certain glasses have been developed to be able to adjust to a broad range of frequencies.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The principle made its public debut remarkably early.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1922, the Teleview 3-D system was installed in a single theater in New York City.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Several short films and one feature-length film were shown by running left-eye and right-eye prints in a pair of interlocked projectors with their shutters operating out of phase.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Each seat in the auditorium was equipped with a viewing device containing a rapidly rotating mechanical shutter synchronized with the projector shutters.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The system worked, but the expense of the installation and the unwieldiness of the viewers, which had to be supported on adjustable stands, confined its use to this one engagement.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In recent decades, the availability of lightweight optoelectronic shutters has led to an updated revival of this display method.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Liquid crystal shutter glasses were first invented by Stephen McAllister of Evans and Sutherland Computer Corporation in the mid-1970s.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The prototype had the LCDs mounted to a small cardboard box using duct tape.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The glasses were never commercialized due to ghosting, but E&S was a very early adopter of third-party glasses such as the StereoGraphics CrystalEyes in the mid-1980s.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Panasonic developed a 3D television that employed active-shutter technology in the late 1970s.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] They unveiled the television in 1981, while at the same time adapting the technology for use with the first stereoscopic video game, Sega's arcade game *SubRoc-3D* (1982).
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1985, 3-D VHD players became available in Japan from manufacturers such as Victor (JVC), National (Panasonic), and Sharp.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Other units were available for field sequential VHS tapes including the Realeyes 3-D.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] A few kits were made available to watch field sequential DVDs.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Sensio released their own format which was higher quality than the High Quality Field Sequential (HQFS) DVDs.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The method of alternating frames can be used to render modern 3-D games into true 3D, although a similar method involving alternate fields has been used to give a 3-D illusion on consoles as old as the Master System and Family Computer.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Special software or hardware is used to generate two channels of images, offset from each other to create the stereoscopic effect.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] High frame rates (typically ~100fps) are required to produce seamless graphics, as the perceived frame rate will be half the actual rate (each eye sees only half the total number of frames).
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Again, LCD shutter glasses synchronized with the graphics chip complete the effect.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1982, Sega's arcade video game *SubRoc-3D* came with a special 3-D eyepiece, which was a viewer with spinning discs to alternate left and right images to the player's eye from a single monitor.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The game's active shutter 3-D system was developed by Sega with Matsushita (now Panasonic).
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1984, Milton Bradley released the 3-D Imager, a primitive form of active shutter glasses that used a motorized rotating disc with transparencies as physical shutters, for the Vectrex.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Although bulky and crude, they used the same basic principle of rapidly alternating imagery that modern active shutter glasses still use.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Nintendo released the Famicom 3D System for the Famicom in October 1987 in Japan, which was an LCD shutter headset, the first home video game electronic device to use LCD Active Shutter glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Sega released the SegaScope 3-D for the Master System Worldwide in November 1987.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Only eight 3-D compatible games were ever released.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1993, Pioneer released the LaserActive system which had a bay for various "PAC's" such as the Mega LD PAC and LD-ROM² PAC.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The unit was 3-D capable with the addition of the LaserActive 3-D goggles (GOL-1) and the adapter (ADP-1).
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1999–2000, a number of companies created stereoscopic LC shutter glasses kits for the Windows PCs which worked with application and games written for Direct3D and OpenGL 3D graphics APIs.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] These kits only worked with CRT computer displays and employed either VGA pass-through, VESA Stereo or proprietary interface for left–right synchronization.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The most prominent example was the ELSA Revelator glasses, which worked exclusively with Nvidia cards through a proprietary interface based on VESA Stereo.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Nvidia later bought the technology and used it in its stereo driver for Windows.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The glasses kits came with driver software which intercepted API calls and effectively rendering the two views in sequence; this technique required twice the performance from the graphic card, so a high-end device was needed.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Visual glitches were common, as many 3-D game engines relied on 2-D effects which were rendered at the incorrect depth, causing disorientation for the viewer.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Very few CRT displays were able to support a 120 Hz refresh rate at common gaming resolutions of the time, so high-end CRT display was required for a flicker-free image; and even with a capable CRT monitor, many users reported flickering and headaches.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] These CRT kits were entirely incompatible with common LCD monitors which had low 60 Hz or 75 Hz refresh rates, unlike CRT displays that had a higher refresh rate at lower resolutions.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Moreover, the display market swiftly shifted to LCD monitors and most display makers ceased production of CRT monitors in early 2000s, which meant that PC glasses kits shortly fell into disuse and were reduced to a very niche market, requiring a purchase of a used high-end, big diagonal CRT monitor.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] SplitFish EyeFX 3-D was a stereo 3-D shutter glasses kit for the Sony PlayStation 2 released in 2005; it only supported standard-definition CRT TVs.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The kit arrived too late in the product cycle of the console when it was effectively replaced by the PlayStation 3, and only a few games were supported, so it was largely ignored by gamers.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The USB-based Nvidia 3D Vision kit released in 2008 supports CRT monitors capable of 100, 110, or 120 Hz refresh rates, as well as 120 Hz LCD monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] There are many sources of low-cost 3-D glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] IO glasses are the most common glasses in this category.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] XpanD 3D is a manufacturer of shutter glasses, with over 1000 theaters currently using XpanD glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] With the release of this technology to the home-viewer market as of 2009, many other manufacturers are now developing their own LC shutter glasses, such as Unipolar International Limited, Accupix Co., Ltd, Panasonic, Samsung, and Sony.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The M-3DI Standard, announced by Panasonic Corporation together with XPAND 3D in March 2011, aims to provide industry-wide compatibility and standardization of LC (Active) Shutter Glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Samsung has developed active 3D glasses that are 2 ounces (57 g) and utilize lens and frame technology pioneered by Silhouette, who creates glasses for NASA.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Nvidia makes a 3-D Vision kit for the PC; it comes with 3-D shutter glasses, a transmitter, and special graphics driver software.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] While regular LCD monitors run at 60 Hz, a 120 Hz monitor is required to use 3-D Vision.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Other well-known providers of active 3-D glasses include EStar America and Optoma.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Both companies produce 3D Glasses compatible with a variety of technologies, including RF, DLP Link and Bluetooth.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In 2007, Texas Instruments introduced stereo 3-D capable Digital Light Processing (DLP) solutions to its OEMs, Samsung and Mitsubishi then introduced the first 3-D ready DLP televisions, and DLP 3-D projectors came later.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] These solutions utilize the inherent speed advantage of the Digital Micro-mirror Device (DMD) to sequentially generate a high refresh rate for the left and right views required for stereoscopic imaging.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] DLP 3-D technology uses the SmoothPicture wobulation algorithm and relies on the properties of modern 1080p60 DMD imagers.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] It effectively compacts two L/R views into a single frame by using a checkerboard pattern, only requiring a standard 1080p60 resolution for stereoscopic transmission to the TV.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The claimed advantage of this solution is increased spatial resolution, unlike other methods which cut vertical or horizontal resolution in half.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The micromirrors are organized in a so-called "offset-diamond pixel layout" of 960×1080 micromirrors, rotated 45 degrees, with their center points placed in the center of "black" squares on the checkerboard.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The DMD employs full-pixel wobulation to display the complete 1080p image as two half-resolution images in a fast sequence.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The DMD operates at twice the refresh rate, i.e.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] 120 Hz, and the complete 1080p picture is displayed in two steps.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] On the first cadence, only half of the original 1080p60 image is displayed – the pixels that correspond to the "black" squares of the checkerboard pattern.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] On the second cadence, the DMD array is mechanically shifted ("wobulated") by one pixel, so the micromirrors are now in a position previously occupied by the gaps, and another half of the image is displayed – this time, the pixels that correspond to the "white" squares.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] A synchronization signal is then generated to synchronize the screen's refresh with LC shutter glasses worn by the viewer, using Texas Instruments' proprietary mechanism called DLP Link.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] DLP Link keeps sync by embedding briefly-flashed white frames during the display's blanking interval, which are picked up by the LC shutter glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Plasma display panels are inherently high-speed devices as well, since they use pulse-width modulation to maintain the brightness of individual pixels, making them compatible with sequential method involving shutter glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Modern panels feature pixel driving frequency of up to 600 Hz and allow 10-bit to 12-bit color precision with 1024 to 4096 gradations of brightness for each subpixel.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Samsung Electronics launched 3D-ready PDP TVs in 2008, a "PAVV Cannes 450" in Korea and PNAx450 in the UK and the US.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The sets utilize the same checkerboard pattern compression scheme as their DLP TVs, though only at the native resolution of 1360×768 pixels and not at HDTV standard 720p, making them only usable with a PC.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Matsushita Electric (Panasonic) prototyped the "3-D Full-HD Plasma Theater System" on CES 2008.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The system is a combination of a 103-inch PDP TV, a Blu-ray Disc player and shutter glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The new system transmits 1080i60 interlaced images for both right and left eyes, and the video is stored on a 50-gigabyte Blu-ray using the MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 compression Multiview Video Coding extension.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Formerly, LCDs were not very suitable for stereoscopic 3-D due to slow pixel response time.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Liquid crystal displays have traditionally been slow to change from one polarization state to another.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Users of early 1990s laptops are familiar with the smearing and blurring that occurs when something moves too fast for the LCD to keep up.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] LCD technology is not usually rated by frames per second but rather the time it takes to transition from one pixel color value to another pixel color value.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Normally, a 120 Hz refresh is displayed for a full 1/120 second (8.33 milliseconds) due to sample-and-hold, regardless of how quickly an LCD can complete pixel transitions.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Recently, it became possible to hide pixel transitions from being seen, using strobe backlight technology, by turning off the backlight between refreshes, to reduce crosstalk.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Newer LCD televisions, including high-end Sony and Samsung 3D TVs, now utilize a strobed backlight or scanning backlight to reduce 3D crosstalk during shutter glasses operation.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In vision therapy of amblyopia and of intermittent central suppression, liquid crystal devices have been used for purposes of enhanced occlusion therapy.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] In this scenario, the amblyopic patient wears electronically programmable liquid crystal glasses or goggles continuously for several hours during regular everyday activities.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] Wearing the device encourages or forces the patient to use both eyes alternatingly, similar to eye patching, but rapidly alternating in time.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The aim is to circumvent the patient's tendency to suppress the field of view of the weaker eye and to train the patient's capacity for binocular vision.
[src:computer-monitor/active-shutter-3d-system] The goggles mostly feature a much slower flicker rate than the more well-known active shutter 3-D glasses.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] The **Adobe RGB (1998) color space** or **opRGB** is a color space developed by Adobe Inc. in 1998.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] It was designed to encompass most of the colors achievable on CMYK color printers, but by using RGB primary colors on a device such as a computer display.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] The Adobe RGB (1998) color space encompasses roughly 30% of the visible colors specified by the CIELAB color space – improving upon the gamut of the sRGB color space, primarily in cyan-green hues.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] It was subsequently standardized by the IEC as IEC 61966-2-5:1999 with a name opRGB (optional RGB color space) and is used in HDMI.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Beginning in 1997, Adobe Systems was looking into creating ICC profiles that its consumers could use in conjunction with Photoshop's new color management features.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Since not many applications at the time had any ICC color management, most operating systems did not ship with useful profiles.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Lead developer of Photoshop, Thomas Knoll decided to build an ICC profile around specifications he found in the documentation for the SMPTE 240M standard, the precursor to Rec.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] 709 (but not in primaries: 240M also defined EOTF and thus was display referred, sRGB was created by connecting BT.470 PAL and SMPTE C).
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] SMPTE 240M's gamut is wider than that of the BT.709 gamut and the same as SMPTE ST 170 also known as SMPTE C.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] However, with the release of Photoshop 5.0 nearing, Adobe made the decision to include the profile within the software.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Although users loved the wider range of reproducible colors, those familiar with the SMPTE 240M specifications contacted Adobe, informing the company that it had copied the values that described idealized primaries, not actual standard ones (in a special annex to the standard).
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] The real values were much closer to sRGB's, which avid Photoshop consumers did not enjoy as a working environment.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] To make matters worse, Thomas Knoll had made an error when copying the red primary chromaticity coordinates, resulting in an even more inaccurate representation of the SMPTE standard.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] On the other hand red and blue primaries are the same as in PAL and green is the same as in NTSC 1953 (blue is the same as in BT.709 and sRGB).
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Adobe tried numerous tactics to correct the profile, such as correcting the red primary and changing the white point to match that of the CIE Standard Illuminant D50 (though that will also change the primaries and is thus pointless), yet all of the adjustments made CMYK conversion worse than before.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] In the end, Adobe decided to keep the "incorrect" profile, but changed the name to *Adobe RGB (1998)* in order to avoid a trademark search or infringement.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] In Adobe RGB (1998), colors are specified as [*R*,*G*,*B*] triplets, where each of the *R*, *G*, and *B* components have values ranging between 0 and 1.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] When displayed on a monitor, the exact chromaticities of the reference white point [1,1,1], the reference black point [0,0,0], and the primaries ([1,0,0], [0,1,0], and [0,0,1]) are specified.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] To meet the color appearance requirements of the color space, the luminance of the monitor must be 160.00 cd/m2 at the white point, and 0.5557 cd/m2 at the black point, which implies a contrast ratio of 287.9.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Moreover, the black point shall have the same chromaticity as the white point, yet with a luminance equal to 0.34731% of the white point luminance.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] The ambient illumination level at the monitor faceplate when the monitor is turned off must be 32 lx.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] As with sRGB, the *RGB* component values in Adobe RGB (1998) are not proportional to the luminances.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Rather, a gamma of approximately 2.2 is assumed, without the linear segment near zero that is present in sRGB.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] In coverage of the CIE 1931 color space the Adobe RGB (1998) color space covers 52.1%.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] where *XKYKZK* and *XWYWZW* are reference display black and white points in the table above.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] As was later defined in the IEC standard opYCC uses BT.601 matrix for conversion to YCbCr, that can be full range matrix and limited range matrix.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Display can signal YCC quantization range support and sink can send either one.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] An image in the ICC Profile Connection Space (PCS) is encoded in 24-bit Adobe RGB (1998) color image encoding.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] The component values would be clipped to the range [0, 1].
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] The resulting component values would be then represented in floating point or integer encodings.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] sRGB is an RGB color space proposed by HP and Microsoft in 1996 to approximate the color gamut of the (then) most common computer display devices (CRTs).
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Adobe RGB (1998) extends into richer cyans and greens than does sRGB – for all levels of luminance.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] The two gamuts are often compared in mid-tone values (~50% luminance), but clear differences are evident in shadows (~25% luminance) and highlights (~75% luminance) as well.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] In fact, Adobe RGB (1998) expands its advantages to areas of intense orange, yellow, and magenta regions.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Also, although Adobe RGB (1998) can *theoretically* represent a wider gamut of colors, the color space requires special software and a complex workflow in order to utilize its full range.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Otherwise, the produced colors would be squeezed into a smaller range (making them appear duller) in order to match sRGB's more widely used gamut.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Although the Adobe RGB (1998) working space clearly provides more colors to utilize, another factor to consider when choosing between color spaces is how each space influences the distribution of the image's bit depth.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] Color spaces with larger gamuts "stretch" the bits over a broader region of colors, whereas smaller gamuts concentrate these bits within a narrow region.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] A similar, yet not as dramatic concentration of bit depth occurs with Adobe RGB (1998) versus sRGB, except in three dimensions rather than one.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] The Adobe RGB (1998) color space occupies roughly 40% more volume than the sRGB color space, which concludes that one would only be exploiting 70% of the available bit depth if the colors in Adobe RGB (1998) are unnecessary.
[src:computer-monitor/adobe-rgb] On the contrary, one may have plenty of "spare" bits if using a 16-bit image, thus negating any reduction due to the choice of working space.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] An **anti-reflective** (**AR**), **anti-glare** or **anti-reflection** **coating** is a type of optical coating applied to the surface of lenses, other optical elements, and photovoltaic cells to reduce reflection.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In typical imaging systems, this improves the efficiency since less light is lost due to reflection.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In complex systems such as cameras, binoculars, telescopes, and microscopes the reduction in reflections also improves the contrast of the image by elimination of stray light.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This is especially important in planetary astronomy.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In other applications, the primary benefit is the elimination of the reflection itself, such as a coating on eyeglass lenses that makes the eyes of the wearer more visible to others, or a coating to reduce the glint from a covert viewer's binoculars or telescopic sight.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Many coatings consist of transparent thin film structures with alternating layers of contrasting refractive index.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Layer thicknesses are chosen to produce destructive interference in the beams reflected from the interfaces, and constructive interference in the corresponding transmitted beams.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This makes the structure's performance change with wavelength and incident angle, so that color effects often appear at oblique angles.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] A wavelength range must be specified when designing or ordering such coatings, but good performance can often be achieved for a relatively wide range of frequencies: usually a choice of IR, visible, or UV is offered.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Anti-reflective coatings are used in a wide variety of applications where light passes through an optical surface, and low loss or low reflection is desired.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Examples include anti-glare coatings on corrective lenses and camera lens elements, and antireflective coatings on solar cells.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Opticians may recommend "anti-reflection lenses" because the decreased reflection enhances the cosmetic appearance of the lenses.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Such lenses are often said to reduce glare, but the reduction is very slight.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Eliminating reflections allows slightly more light to pass through, producing a slight increase in contrast and visual acuity.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Antireflective ophthalmic lenses should not be confused with polarized lenses, which are found only in sunglasses and decrease (by absorption) the visible glare of sun reflected off surfaces such as sand, water, and roads.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The term "antireflective" relates to the reflection from the surface of the lens itself, not the origin of the light that reaches the lens.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Many anti-reflection lenses include an additional coating that repels water and grease, making them easier to keep clean.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Anti-reflection coatings are particularly suited to high-index lenses, as these reflect more light without the coating than a lower-index lens (a consequence of the Fresnel equations).
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] It is also generally easier and cheaper to coat high index lenses.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Antireflective coatings (ARC) are often used in microelectronic photolithography to help reduce image distortions associated with reflections off the surface of the substrate.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Different types of antireflective coatings are applied either before (Bottom ARC, or BARC) or after the photoresist, and help reduce standing waves, thin-film interference, and specular reflections.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Solar cells are often coated with an anti-reflective coating.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Materials that have been used include magnesium fluoride, silicon nitride, silicon dioxide, titanium dioxide, and aluminum oxide.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The simplest form of anti-reflective coating was discovered by Lord Rayleigh in 1886.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The optical glass available at the time tended to develop a tarnish on its surface with age, due to chemical reactions with the environment.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Rayleigh tested some old, slightly tarnished pieces of glass, and found to his surprise that they transmitted *more* light than new, clean pieces.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The tarnish replaces the air-glass interface with two interfaces: an air-tarnish interface and a tarnish-glass interface.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Because the tarnish has a refractive index between those of glass and air, each of these interfaces exhibits less reflection than the air-glass interface did.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In fact, the total of the two reflections is less than that of the "naked" air-glass interface, as can be calculated from the Fresnel equations.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] One approach is to use graded-index (GRIN) anti-reflective coatings, that is, ones with nearly continuously varying indices of refraction.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] With these, it is possible to curtail reflection for a broad band of frequencies and incidence angles.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The simplest interference anti-reflective coating consists of a single thin layer of transparent material with refractive index equal to the square root of the substrate's refractive index.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In air, such a coating theoretically gives zero reflectance for light with wavelength (in the coating) equal to four times the coating's thickness.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Reflectance is also decreased for wavelengths in a broad band around the center.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] A layer of thickness equal to a quarter of some design wavelength is called a "quarter-wave layer".
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The most common type of optical glass is crown glass, which has an index of refraction of about 1.52.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] An optimal single-layer coating would have to be made of a material with an index of about 1.23.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] There are no solid materials with such a low refractive index.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The closest materials with good physical properties for a coating are magnesium fluoride, MgF2 (with an index of 1.38), and fluoropolymers, which can have indices as low as 1.30, but are more difficult to apply.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] MgF2 on a crown glass surface gives a reflectance of about 1%, compared to 4% for bare glass.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] MgF2 coatings perform much better on higher-index glasses, especially those with index of refraction close to 1.9.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] MgF2 coatings are commonly used because they are cheap and durable.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] When the coatings are designed for a wavelength in the middle of the visible band, they give reasonably good anti-reflection over the entire band.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Researchers have produced films of mesoporous silica nanoparticles with refractive indices as low as 1.12, which function as antireflection coatings.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] By using alternating layers of a low-index material like silica and a higher-index material, it is possible to obtain reflectivities as low as 0.1% at a single wavelength.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Coatings that give very low reflectivity over a broad band of frequencies can also be made, although these are complex and relatively expensive.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Optical coatings can also be made with special characteristics, such as near-zero reflectance at multiple wavelengths, or optimal performance at angles of incidence other than 0°.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] An additional category of anti-reflection coatings is the so-called "absorbing ARC".
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] These coatings are useful in situations where high transmission through a surface is unimportant or undesirable, but low reflectivity is required.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] They can produce very low reflectance with few layers, and can often be produced more cheaply, or at greater scale, than standard non-absorbing AR coatings.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] (See, for example, US Patent 5,091,244.) Absorbing ARCs often make use of unusual optical properties exhibited in compound thin films produced by sputter deposition.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] For example, titanium nitride and niobium nitride are used in absorbing ARCs.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] These can be useful in applications requiring contrast enhancement or as a replacement for tinted glass (for example, in a CRT display).
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Moths' eyes have an unusual property: their surfaces are covered with a natural nanostructured film, which eliminates reflections.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This allows the moth to see well in the dark, without reflections to give its location away to predators.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The structure consists of a hexagonal pattern of bumps, each roughly 200 nm high and spaced on 300 nm centers.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This kind of antireflective coating works because the bumps are smaller than the wavelength of visible light, so the light sees the surface as having a continuous refractive index gradient between the air and the medium, which decreases reflection by effectively removing the air-lens interface.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Practical anti-reflective films have been made by humans using this effect; this is a form of biomimicry.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Canon uses the moth-eye technique in their SWC subwavelength structure coating, which significantly reduces lens flare.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Such structures are also used in photonic devices, for example, moth-eye structures grown from tungsten oxide and iron oxide can be used as photoelectrodes for splitting water to produce hydrogen.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The structure consists of tungsten oxide spheroids several hundred micrometers in diameter, coated with a few nanometers of iron oxide.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] A circular polarizer laminated to a surface can be used to eliminate reflections.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The polarizer transmits light with one chirality ("handedness") of circular polarization.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Light reflected from the surface after the polarizer is transformed into the opposite "handedness".
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This light cannot pass back through the circular polarizer because its chirality has changed (e.g. from right circular polarized to left circularly polarized).
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] A disadvantage of this method is that if the input light is unpolarized, the transmission through the assembly will be less than 50%.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] There are two separate causes of optical effects due to coatings, often called *thick-film* and *thin-film* effects.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Thick-film effects arise because of the difference in the index of refraction between the layers above and below the coating (or *film*); in the simplest case, these three layers are the air, the coating, and the glass.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Thick-film coatings do not depend on how thick the coating is, so long as the coating is much thicker than a wavelength of light.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Thin-film effects arise when the thickness of the coating is approximately the same as a quarter or a half a wavelength of light.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In this case, the reflections of a steady source of light can be made to add destructively and hence reduce reflections by a separate mechanism.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In addition to depending very much on the thickness of the film and the wavelength of light, thin-film coatings depend on the angle at which the light strikes the coated surface.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Whenever a ray of light moves from one medium to another (for example, when light enters a sheet of glass after travelling through air), some portion of the light is reflected from the surface (known as the *interface*) between the two media.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This can be observed when looking through a window, for instance, where a (weak) reflection from the front and back surfaces of the window glass can be seen.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The strength of the reflection depends on the ratio of the refractive indices of the two media, as well as the angle of the surface to the beam of light.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The exact value can be calculated using the Fresnel equations.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] where *n*0 and *n*S are the refractive indices of the first and second media respectively.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The value of *R* varies from 0 (no reflection) to 1 (all light reflected) and is usually quoted as a percentage.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Complementary to *R* is the *transmission coefficient*, or *transmittance*, *T*.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] If absorption and scattering are neglected, then the value *T* is always 1 − *R*.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Thus if a beam of light with intensity *I* is incident on the surface, a beam of intensity *RI* is reflected, and a beam with intensity *TI* is transmitted into the medium.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] For the simplified scenario of visible light travelling from air (*n*0 ≈ 1.0) into common glass (*n*S ≈ 1.5), the value of *R* is 0.04, or 4%, on a single reflection.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] So at most 96% of the light (*T* = 1 − *R* = 0.96) actually enters the glass, and the rest is reflected from the surface.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The amount of light reflected is known as the *reflection loss*.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In the more complicated scenario of multiple reflections, say with light travelling through a window, light is reflected both when going from air to glass and at the other side of the window when going from glass back to air.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The size of the loss is the same in both cases.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Light also may bounce from one surface to another multiple times, being partially reflected and partially transmitted each time it does so.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In all, the combined reflection coefficient is given by 2*R*/(1 + *R*).
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] As observed by Lord Rayleigh, a thin film (such as tarnish) on the surface of glass can reduce the reflectivity.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This effect can be explained by envisioning a thin layer of material with refractive index *n*1 between the air (index *n*0) and the glass (index *n*S).
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The light ray now reflects twice: once from the surface between air and the thin layer, and once from the layer-to-glass interface.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] From the equation above and the known refractive indices, reflectivities for both interfaces can be calculated, denoted *R*01 and *R*1S respectively.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The transmission at each interface is therefore *T*01 = 1 − *R*01 and *T*1S = 1 − *R*1S.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The total transmittance into the glass is thus *T*1S*T*01.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Calculating this value for various values of *n*1, it can be found that at one particular value of optimal refractive index of the layer, the transmittance of both interfaces is equal, and this corresponds to the maximal total transmittance into the glass.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] For the example of glass (*n*S ≈ 1.5) in air (*n*0 ≈ 1.0), this optimal refractive index is *n*1 ≈ 1.225.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The reflection loss of each interface is approximately 1.0% (with a combined loss of 2.0%), and an overall transmission *T*1S*T*01 of approximately 98%.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Therefore, an intermediate coating between the air and glass can halve the reflection loss.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The use of an intermediate layer to form an anti-reflection coating can be thought of as analogous to the technique of impedance matching of electrical signals.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Practical anti-reflection coatings, however, rely on an intermediate layer not only for its direct reduction of reflection coefficient, but also use the interference effect of a thin layer.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Assume the layer's thickness is controlled precisely, such that it is exactly one quarter of the wavelength of light in the layer (λ/4 = λ0/(4*n*1), where λ0 is the vacuum wavelength).
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The layer is then called a *quarter-wave coating*.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] For this type of coating a normally incident beam *I*, when reflected from the second interface, will travel exactly half its own wavelength further than the beam reflected from the first surface, leading to destructive interference.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This is also true for thicker coating layers (3λ/4, 5λ/4, etc.), however the anti-reflective performance is worse in this case due to the stronger dependence of the reflectance on wavelength and the angle of incidence.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] If the intensities of the two beams *R*1 and *R*2 are exactly equal, they will destructively interfere and cancel each other, since they are exactly out of phase.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Therefore, there is no reflection from the surface, and all the energy of the beam must be in the transmitted ray, *T*.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In the calculation of the reflection from a stack of layers, the transfer-matrix method can be used.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Real coatings do not reach perfect performance, though they are capable of reducing a surface reflection coefficient to less than 0.1%.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Also, the layer will have the ideal thickness for only one distinct wavelength of light.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Other difficulties include finding suitable materials for use on ordinary glass, since few useful substances have the required refractive index (*n* ≈ 1.23) that will make both reflected rays exactly equal in intensity.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Magnesium fluoride (MgF2) is often used, since this is hard-wearing and can be easily applied to substrates using physical vapor deposition, even though its index is higher than desirable (*n* = 1.38).
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Further reduction is possible by using multiple coating layers, designed such that reflections from the surfaces undergo maximal destructive interference.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] One way to do this is to add a second quarter-wave thick higher-index layer between the low-index layer and the substrate.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The reflection from all three interfaces produces destructive interference and anti-reflection.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Other techniques use varying thicknesses of the coatings.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] By using two or more layers, each of a material chosen to give the best possible match of the desired refractive index and dispersion, broadband anti-reflection coatings covering the visible range (400–700 nm) with maximal reflectivity of less than 0.5% are commonly achievable.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The exact nature of the coating determines the appearance of the coated optic; common AR coatings on eyeglasses and photographic lenses often look somewhat bluish (since they reflect slightly more blue light than other visible wavelengths), though green and pink-tinged coatings are also used.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] If the coated optic is used at non-normal incidence (that is, with light rays not perpendicular to the surface), the anti-reflection capabilities are degraded somewhat.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This occurs because the phase accumulated in the layer *relative to the phase of the light immediately reflected* decreases as the angle increases from normal.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This is counterintuitive, since the ray experiences a greater total phase shift in the layer than for normal incidence.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] This paradox is resolved by noting that the ray will exit the layer spatially offset from where it entered and will interfere with reflections from incoming rays that had to travel further (thus accumulating more phase of their own) to arrive at the interface.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] The net effect is that the relative phase is actually reduced, shifting the coating, such that the anti-reflection band of the coating tends to move to shorter wavelengths as the optic is tilted.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Non-normal incidence angles also usually cause the reflection to be polarization-dependent.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Reflection can be reduced by texturing the surface with 3D pyramids or 2D grooves (gratings).This kind of textured coating can be created using for example the Langmuir-Blodgett method.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] If wavelength is greater than the texture size, the texture behaves like a gradient-index film with reduced reflection.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] To calculate reflection in this case, effective medium approximations can be used.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] To minimize reflection, various profiles of pyramids have been proposed, such as cubic, quintic or integral exponential profiles.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] If wavelength is smaller than the textured size, the reflection reduction can be explained with the help of the geometric optics approximation: rays should be reflected many times before they are sent back toward the source.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In this case the reflection can be calculated using ray tracing.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Using texture reduces reflection for wavelengths comparable with the feature size as well.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In this case no approximation is valid, and reflection can be calculated by solving Maxwell equations numerically.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Antireflective properties of textured surfaces are well discussed in literature for a wide range of size-to-wavelength ratios (including long- and short-wave limits) to find the optimal texture size.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] As mentioned above, natural index-matching "coatings" were discovered by Lord Rayleigh in 1886.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Harold Dennis Taylor of Cooke company developed a chemical method for producing such coatings in 1904.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Interference-based coatings were invented and developed in 1935 by Olexander Smakula, who was working for the Carl Zeiss optics company.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] These coatings remained a German military secret for several years, until the Allies discovered the secret at the end of World War II.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] Katharine Burr Blodgett and Irving Langmuir developed organic anti-reflection coatings known as Langmuir–Blodgett films in the late 1930s.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] In 1938, 17 coating plants were operating, but were limited to military applications only.
[src:computer-monitor/anti-reflective-coating] These coatings became generally available in the 1940s, with the coated Zeiss Biotar and Sonnar lenses being presented at the Leipzig Spring Fair in 1940.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A **computer monitor** is an output device that displays information in pictorial or textual form.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A discrete monitor comprises a visual display, support electronics, power supply, housing, electrical connectors, and external user controls.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The display in modern monitors is typically an LCD with LED backlight, having by the 2010s replaced CCFL backlit LCDs.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Before the mid-2000s, most monitors used a cathode ray tube (CRT) as the image output technology.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A monitor is typically connected to its host computer via DisplayPort, HDMI, USB-C, DVI, or VGA.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Monitors sometimes use other proprietary connectors and signals to connect to a computer, which is less common.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Originally computer monitors were used for data processing while television sets were used for video.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] From the 1980s onward, computers (and their monitors) have been used for both data processing and video, while television sets have implemented some computer functionality.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Modern computer monitors are often functionally interchangeable with television sets and vice versa.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] As most computer monitors do not include integrated speakers, TV tuners, or remote controls, external components such as a DTA box may be needed to use a computer monitor as a TV set.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Early electronic computer front panels were fitted with an array of light bulbs where the state of each particular bulb would indicate the on/off state of a particular register bit inside the computer.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This allowed the engineers operating the computer to monitor the internal state of the machine, so this panel of lights came to be known as the 'monitor'.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] As early monitors were only capable of displaying a very limited amount of information and were very transient, they were rarely considered for program output.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Instead, a line printer was the primary output device, while the monitor was limited to keeping track of the program's operation.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Computer monitors were formerly known as **visual display units** (**VDU**), particularly in British English.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This term mostly fell out of use by the 1990s.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Multiple technologies have been used for computer monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Until the 21st century most used cathode ray tubes but they have largely been superseded by LCD monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The first computer monitors used cathode ray tubes (CRTs).
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The display was monochromatic and far less sharp and detailed than on a modern monitor, necessitating the use of relatively large text and severely limiting the amount of information that could be displayed at one time.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] High-resolution CRT displays were developed for specialized military, industrial and scientific applications but they were far too costly for general use; wider commercial use became possible after the release of a slow, but affordable Tektronix 4010 terminal in 1972.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Either computer could be connected to the antenna terminals of an ordinary color TV set or used with a purpose-made CRT color monitor for optimum resolution and color quality.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Lagging several years behind, in 1981 IBM introduced the Color Graphics Adapter, which could display four colors with a resolution of 320 × 200 pixels, or it could produce 640 × 200 pixels with two colors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] In 1984 IBM introduced the Enhanced Graphics Adapter which was capable of producing 16 colors and had a resolution of 640 × 350.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] During the following decade, maximum display resolutions gradually increased and prices continued to fall as CRT technology remained dominant in the PC monitor market into the new millennium, partly because it remained cheaper to produce.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] CRTs still offer color, grayscale, motion, and latency advantages over today's LCDs, but improvements to the latter have made them much less obvious.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The dynamic range of early LCD panels was very poor, and although text and other motionless graphics were sharper than on a CRT, an LCD characteristic known as pixel lag caused moving graphics to appear noticeably smeared and blurry.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] There are multiple technologies that have been used to implement liquid-crystal displays (LCD).
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Throughout the 1990s, the primary use of LCD technology as computer monitors was in laptops where the lower power consumption, lighter weight, and smaller physical size of LCDs justified the higher price versus a CRT.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Commonly, the same laptop would be offered with an assortment of display options at increasing price points: (active or passive) monochrome, passive color, or active matrix color (TFT).
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] As volume and manufacturing capability have improved, the monochrome and passive color technologies were dropped from most product lines.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] TFT-LCD is a variant of LCD which is now the dominant technology used for computer monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The first standalone LCDs appeared in the mid-1990s selling for high prices.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] As prices declined they became more popular, and by 1997 were competing with CRT monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Among the first desktop LCD computer monitors were the Eizo FlexScan L66 in the mid-1990s, the SGI 1600SW, Apple Studio Display and the ViewSonic VP140 in 1998.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] In 2003, LCDs outsold CRTs for the first time, becoming the primary technology used for computer monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The physical advantages of LCD over CRT monitors are that LCDs are lighter, smaller, and consume less power.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] In terms of performance, LCDs produce less or no flicker, reducing eyestrain, sharper image at native resolution, and better checkerboard contrast.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Many specialized fields such as vision science remain dependent on CRTs, the best LCD monitors having achieved moderate temporal accuracy, and so can be used only if their poor spatial accuracy is unimportant.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] High dynamic range (HDR) has been implemented into high-end LCD monitors to improve grayscale accuracy.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Since around the late 2000s, widescreen LCD monitors have become popular, in part due to television series, motion pictures and video games transitioning to widescreen, which makes squarer monitors unsuited to display them correctly.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Organic light-emitting diode (OLED) monitors provide most of the benefits of both LCD and CRT monitors with few of their drawbacks, though much like plasma panels or CRTs they suffer from burn-in, and are comparatively more expensive.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] On two-dimensional display devices such as computer monitors the display size or viewable image size is the actual amount of screen space that is available to display a picture, video or working space, without obstruction from the bezel or other aspects of the unit's design.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The main measurements for display devices are width, height, total area and the diagonal.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The size of a display is usually given by manufacturers diagonally, i.e. as the distance between two opposite screen corners.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This method of measurement is inherited from the method used for the first generation of CRT television when picture tubes with circular faces were in common use.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Being circular, it was the external diameter of the glass envelope that described their size.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Since these circular tubes were used to display rectangular images, the diagonal measurement of the rectangular image was smaller than the diameter of the tube's face (due to the thickness of the glass).
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This method continued even when cathode ray tubes were manufactured as rounded rectangles; it had the advantage of being a single number specifying the size and was not confusing when the aspect ratio was universally 4:3.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] With the introduction of flat-panel technology, the diagonal measurement became the actual diagonal of the visible display.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This meant that an eighteen-inch LCD had a larger viewable area than an eighteen-inch cathode ray tube.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Estimation of monitor size by the distance between opposite corners does not take into account the display aspect ratio, so that for example a 16:9 21-inch (53 cm) widescreen display has less area, than a 21-inch (53 cm) 4:3 screen.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Until about 2001, most computer monitors had a 4:3 aspect ratio and some had 5:4 or 8:7.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Between 2001 and 2006, monitors with 16:9 and mostly 16:10 (8:5) aspect ratios became commonly available, first in laptops and later also in standalone monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Reasons for this transition included productive uses (i.e. field of view in video games and movie viewing) such as the word processor display of two standard letter pages side by side, as well as CAD displays of large-size drawings and application menus at the same time.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] In 2008 16:10 became the most common sold aspect ratio for LCD monitors and the same year 16:10 was the mainstream standard for laptops and notebook computers.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] In 2010, the computer industry started to move over from 16:10 to 16:9 because 16:9 was chosen to be the standard high-definition television display size, and because they were cheaper to manufacture.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] In 2011, non-widescreen displays with 4:3 aspect ratios were only being manufactured in small quantities.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The resolution for computer monitors has increased over time.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Since 2009, the most commonly sold resolution for computer monitors is 1920 × 1080, shared with the 1080p of HDTV.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Before 2013 mass market LCD monitors were limited to 2560 × 1600 at 30 in (76 cm), excluding niche professional monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] By 2015 most major display manufacturers had released 3840 × 2160 (4K UHD) displays, and the first 7680 × 4320 (8K) monitors had begun shipping.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Every RGB monitor has its own color gamut, bounded in chromaticity by a color triangle.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Some of these triangles are smaller than the sRGB triangle, some are larger.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Colors are typically encoded by 8 bits per primary color.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The RGB value [255, 0, 0] represents red, but slightly different colors in different color spaces such as Adobe RGB and sRGB.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Displaying sRGB-encoded data on wide-gamut devices can give an unrealistic result.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The gamut is a property of the monitor; the image color space can be forwarded as Exif metadata in the picture.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] As long as the monitor gamut is wider than the color space gamut, correct display is possible, if the monitor is calibrated.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A picture that uses colors that are outside the sRGB color space will display on an sRGB color space monitor with limitations.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Still today, many monitors that can display the sRGB color space are not factory nor user-calibrated to display it correctly.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Color management is needed both in electronic publishing (via the Internet for display in browsers) and in desktop publishing targeted to print.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Most modern monitors will switch to a power-saving mode if no video-input signal is received.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This allows modern operating systems to turn off a monitor after a specified period of inactivity.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This also extends the monitor's service life.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Some monitors will also switch themselves off after a time period on standby.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Most modern laptops provide a method of screen dimming after periods of inactivity or when the battery is in use.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This extends battery life and reduces wear.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Most modern monitors have two different indicator light colors wherein if video-input signal was detected, the indicator light is green and when the monitor is in power-saving mode, the screen is black and the indicator light is orange.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Some monitors have different indicator light colors and some monitors have a blinking indicator light when in power-saving mode.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Many monitors have other accessories (or connections for them) integrated.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This places standard ports within easy reach and eliminates the need for another separate hub, camera, microphone, or set of speakers.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] These monitors have advanced microprocessors which contain codec information, Windows interface drivers and other small software which help in proper functioning of these functions.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Monitors that feature an aspect ratio greater than 2:1 (for instance, 21:9 or 32:9, as opposed to the more common 16:9, which resolves to 1.77:1).Monitors with an aspect ratio greater than 3:1 are marketed as super ultrawide monitors.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] These are typically massive curved screens intended to replace a multi-monitor deployment.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] These monitors use touching of the screen as an input method.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Items can be selected or moved with a finger, and finger gestures may be used to convey commands.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The screen will need frequent cleaning due to image degradation from fingerprints.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Some displays, especially newer flat-panel monitors, replace the traditional anti-glare matte finish with a glossy one.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This increases color saturation and sharpness but reflections from lights and windows are more visible.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Anti-reflective coatings are sometimes applied to help reduce reflections, although this only partly mitigates the problem.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Most often using nominally flat-panel display technology such as LCD or OLED, a concave rather than convex curve is imparted, reducing geometric distortion, especially in extremely large and wide seamless desktop monitors intended for close viewing range.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Newer monitors are able to display a different image for each eye, often with the help of special glasses and polarizers, giving the perception of depth.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] An autostereoscopic screen can generate 3D images without headgear.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Features for medical using or for outdoor placement.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Narrow viewing angle screens are used in some security-conscious applications.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Integrated screen calibration tools, screen hoods, signal transmitters; Protective screens.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A combination of a monitor with a graphics tablet.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Such devices are typically unresponsive to touch without the use of one or more special tools' pressure.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Newer models however are now able to detect touch from any pressure and often have the ability to detect tool tilt and rotation as well.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Touch and tablet sensors are often used on sample and hold displays such as LCDs to substitute for the light pen, which can only work on CRTs.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The option for using the display as a reference monitor; these calibration features can give an advanced color management control for take a near-perfect image.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Option for professional LCD monitors, inherent to OLED & CRT; professional feature with mainstream tendency.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Near to mainstream professional feature; advanced hardware driver for backlit modules with local zones of uniformity correction.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Computer monitors are provided with a variety of methods for mounting them depending on the application and environment.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A desktop monitor is typically provided with a stand from the manufacturer which lifts the monitor up to a more ergonomic viewing height.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The stand may be attached to the monitor using a proprietary method or may use, or be adaptable to, a VESA mount.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A VESA standard mount allows the monitor to be used with more after-market stands if the original stand is removed.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Stands may be fixed or offer a variety of features such as height adjustment, horizontal swivel, and landscape or portrait screen orientation.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The Flat Display Mounting Interface (FDMI), also known as VESA Mounting Interface Standard (MIS) or colloquially as a VESA mount, is a family of standards defined by the Video Electronics Standards Association for mounting flat-panel displays to stands or wall mounts.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] It is implemented on most modern flat-panel monitors and TVs.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] For computer monitors, the VESA Mount typically consists of four threaded holes on the rear of the display that will mate with an adapter bracket.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A fixed rack mount monitor is mounted directly to the rack with the flat-panel or CRT visible at all times.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The height of the unit is measured in rack units (RU) and 8U or 9U are most common to fit 17-inch or 19-inch screens.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The front sides of the unit are provided with flanges to mount to the rack, providing appropriately spaced holes or slots for the rack mounting screws.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A 19-inch diagonal screen is the largest size that will fit within the rails of a 19-inch rack.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Larger flat-panels may be accommodated but are 'mount-on-rack' and extend forward of the rack.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] There are smaller display units, typically used in broadcast environments, which fit multiple smaller screens side by side into one rack mount.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A stowable rack mount monitor is 1U, 2U or 3U high and is mounted on rack slides allowing the display to be folded down and the unit slid into the rack for storage as a drawer.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The flat display is visible only when pulled out of the rack and deployed.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] These units may include only a display or may be equipped with a keyboard creating a KVM (Keyboard Video Monitor).
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Most common are systems with a single LCD but there are systems providing two or three displays in a single rack mount system.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A panel mount computer monitor is intended for mounting into a flat surface with the front of the display unit protruding just slightly.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] They may also be mounted to the rear of the panel.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] A flange is provided around the screen, sides, top and bottom, to allow mounting.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] This contrasts with a rack mount display where the flanges are only on the sides.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] The flanges will be provided with holes for thru-bolts or may have studs welded to the rear surface to secure the unit in the hole in the panel.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Often a gasket is provided to provide a water-tight seal to the panel and the front of the screen will be sealed to the back of the front panel to prevent water and dirt contamination.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] An open frame monitor provides the display and enough supporting structure to hold associated electronics and to minimally support the display.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Provision will be made for attaching the unit to some external structure for support and protection.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Open frame monitors are intended to be built into some other piece of equipment providing its own case.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] An arcade video game would be a good example with the display mounted inside the cabinet.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] There is usually an open frame display inside all end-use displays with the end-use display simply providing an attractive protective enclosure.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Some rack mount monitor manufacturers will purchase desktop displays, take them apart, and discard the outer plastic parts, keeping the inner open-frame display for inclusion into their product.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] According to a National Security Agency (NSA) document leaked to *Der Spiegel*, the NSA sometimes swaps the monitor cables on targeted computers with a bugged monitor cable to allow the NSA to remotely see what is being displayed on the targeted computer monitor.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Van Eck phreaking is the process of remotely displaying the contents of a CRT or LCD by detecting its electromagnetic emissions.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] It is named after Dutch computer researcher Wim van Eck, who in 1985 published the first paper on it, including proof of concept.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] While most effective on older CRT monitors due to their strong electromagnetic emissions, it can potentially apply to LCDs as well, although modern shielding techniques significantly mitigate the risk.
[src:computer-monitor/computer-monitor] Phreaking more generally is the process of exploiting telephone networks.
